1
00:00:26,071 --> 00:00:29,073
SIX SINGLES UNDER ONE ROOF

2
00:00:29,074 --> 00:00:30,608
AFTER YEARS OF LIVING ALONE

3
00:00:30,609 --> 00:00:33,277
I'M GETTING HOUSEMATES?

4
00:00:33,278 --> 00:00:35,613
I SHOULD BE ABLE TO BEAR THIS, RIGHT?

5
00:00:35,614 --> 00:00:37,281
HAVING A NEIGHBOR JUST BEHIND A WALL

6
00:00:37,282 --> 00:00:39,251
Silent mode, please.

7
00:00:39,685 --> 00:00:40,719
I'm sorry.

8
00:00:41,153 --> 00:00:44,789
A SHARED BATHROOM

9
00:00:44,790 --> 00:00:47,026
You should lock the door
when you're taking a shower.

10
00:00:47,359 --> 00:00:48,393
Serves you right.

11
00:00:48,394 --> 00:00:49,727
Why did you take a peek?

12
00:00:49,728 --> 00:00:50,828
WHAT'S MINE BECOMES EVERYONE'S

13
00:00:50,829 --> 00:00:52,464
This was filled up to here yesterday.

14
00:00:53,465 --> 00:00:54,766
WHO DRANK THIS?

15
00:00:54,767 --> 00:00:57,002
SEEING EACH OTHER
WITHOUT MAKEUP OR GROOMING

16
00:00:57,636 --> 00:00:59,038
My gosh, Da-hee.

17
00:01:00,139 --> 00:01:01,240
Good morning, guys.

18
00:01:01,607 --> 00:01:03,642
You look rough this morning.

19
00:01:04,810 --> 00:01:06,411
IS THIS THE FUN OF HAVING HOUSEMATES?

20
00:01:06,412 --> 00:01:09,814
A PLEASANT COMPANY
TO SHARE YOUR DINNER

21
00:01:09,815 --> 00:01:11,315
FRIENDS TO TALK TO

22
00:01:11,316 --> 00:01:13,184
It's a joy to come home together.

23
00:01:13,185 --> 00:01:16,155
SHARING DAYS AND NIGHTS TOGETHER

24
00:01:16,689 --> 00:01:19,625
<i>I've never had
an experience like this before.</i>

25
00:01:22,661 --> 00:01:25,063
I NOW HAVE HOUSEMATES

26
00:01:25,064 --> 00:01:28,332
I NOW HAVE FRIENDS CLOSE TO MY AGE

27
00:01:28,333 --> 00:01:29,968
Did you catch the shooting star?

28
00:01:30,536 --> 00:01:31,703
WE'RE GOING TO BUILD A NEW FAMILY

29
00:01:31,704 --> 00:01:33,205
<i>This is what happiness looks like.</i>

30
00:01:33,439 --> 00:01:35,174
Say Gugi!

31
00:01:35,641 --> 00:01:37,775
WHAT WOULD YOU CHOOSE?

32
00:01:37,776 --> 00:01:41,446
LIVING ALONE, LIVING TOGETHER

33
00:01:41,447 --> 00:01:42,980
LIVING TOGETHER

34
00:01:42,981 --> 00:01:48,387
SIX SINGLES UNDER ONE ROOF

35
00:01:49,955 --> 00:01:56,627
GUGI-DONG

36
00:01:56,628 --> 00:01:59,163
ONE DAY IN 2026
GUGI-DONG, JONGNO-GU, SEOUL

37
00:01:59,164 --> 00:02:01,233
A DEEP SIGH

38
00:02:01,700 --> 00:02:02,967
My palms are sweaty.

39
00:02:02,968 --> 00:02:04,036
Oh, man.

40
00:02:05,270 --> 00:02:06,337
WELCOME TO GUGI-DONG HOUSE

41
00:02:06,338 --> 00:02:07,806
I feel nervous.

42
00:02:08,540 --> 00:02:09,808
So nervous.

43
00:02:11,276 --> 00:02:12,276
THE FIRST NERVOUS TENANT HAS ARRIVED

44
00:02:12,277 --> 00:02:13,644
Wish me luck.

45
00:02:13,645 --> 00:02:14,713
I've got this.

46
00:02:17,416 --> 00:02:19,083
Let me take a deep breath first.

47
00:02:19,084 --> 00:02:20,953
NEVER-ENDING RELAXING ATTEMPTS

48
00:02:25,290 --> 00:02:26,557
Hills surround the place.

49
00:02:26,558 --> 00:02:28,025
FINALLY SEEING GUGI-DONG IN PERSON

50
00:02:28,026 --> 00:02:31,296
There's a quiet, peaceful vibe here.

51
00:02:32,464 --> 00:02:33,598
<i>Bukaksan-ro.</i>

52
00:02:33,599 --> 00:02:34,832
GUGI-DONG

53
00:02:34,833 --> 00:02:36,934
RIGHT BELOW THE BUKHAN MOUNTAIN

54
00:02:36,935 --> 00:02:39,004
NEXT TO PYEONGCHANG-DONG

55
00:02:40,239 --> 00:02:41,440
<i>It's nestled at the perfect spot.</i>

56
00:02:42,107 --> 00:02:43,775
<i>Mountains circle the neighborhood.</i>

57
00:02:43,776 --> 00:02:45,476
<i>The surrounding nature is lovely</i>

58
00:02:45,477 --> 00:02:48,781
<i>and I'm happy to be able to see
all the lush greenery.</i>

59
00:02:50,182 --> 00:02:52,550
THE RESIDENTIAL AREA
AT THE FOOT OF THE MOUNTAIN

60
00:02:52,551 --> 00:02:54,719
WITH ITS SPECIAL CHARM

61
00:02:54,720 --> 00:02:57,923
THE FRIENDLY NEIGHBORHOOD

62
00:02:58,657 --> 00:02:59,658
Hold on.

63
00:03:00,592 --> 00:03:01,760
I wonder if someone's home.

64
00:03:05,030 --> 00:03:07,232
JANG KEUN-SUK
SOLO DWELLER OF 14 YEARS

65
00:03:08,567 --> 00:03:09,567
JANG KEUN-SUK

66
00:03:09,568 --> 00:03:11,669
ASIA PRINCE, MISCHIEVOUS CHEF,
LIVE SHARP AND DIE SHARP

67
00:03:11,670 --> 00:03:15,306
I've been on my own for 14 years.

68
00:03:15,307 --> 00:03:16,809
May I ask how old you are?

69
00:03:17,342 --> 00:03:18,509
My age?

70
00:03:18,510 --> 00:03:19,944
Is that important?

71
00:03:19,945 --> 00:03:21,512
I was born in the Year of the Rabbit.

72
00:03:21,513 --> 00:03:22,614
In 1999.

73
00:03:23,448 --> 00:03:26,384
DRIVEN INTO DENIAL
WITH 40 LOOMING OVER HIM

74
00:03:26,385 --> 00:03:27,985
To be honest

75
00:03:27,986 --> 00:03:31,455
I haven't gotten married yet

76
00:03:31,456 --> 00:03:33,758
and my life as a bachelor...

77
00:03:33,759 --> 00:03:35,226
To be perfectly honest with you

78
00:03:35,227 --> 00:03:36,894
I'm not ready to let it go.

79
00:03:36,895 --> 00:03:39,598
I still have so much I want to try

80
00:03:40,132 --> 00:03:41,866
and dreams to achieve.

81
00:03:41,867 --> 00:03:44,869
But as my closest friends got married

82
00:03:44,870 --> 00:03:47,338
and built families of their own

83
00:03:47,339 --> 00:03:50,976
I realized one day
I was the only one still alone.

84
00:03:51,410 --> 00:03:54,345
I could tick off items
from my bucket list all alone

85
00:03:54,346 --> 00:03:56,714
but where's the meaning in that?

86
00:03:56,715 --> 00:04:02,287
I've come to hope for a companion
to join me in my journey.

87
00:04:02,621 --> 00:04:03,721
Am I the first to arrive?

88
00:04:03,722 --> 00:04:05,023
THAT'S WHY HE JOINED THE SHOW

89
00:04:10,362 --> 00:04:11,797
That's impressive.

90
00:04:15,133 --> 00:04:17,436
WELCOME TO YOUR NEW HOME

91
00:04:18,337 --> 00:04:20,405
Let's get going.

92
00:04:23,742 --> 00:04:25,376
AT THE END OF THE SLOPE

93
00:04:25,377 --> 00:04:27,678
IS KEUN-SUK'S NEW HOME

94
00:04:27,679 --> 00:04:29,448
How many floors are there?

95
00:04:30,549 --> 00:04:31,782
A whopping three floors?

96
00:04:31,783 --> 00:04:33,417
AN UNIMAGINABLE PLACE
WHEN LIVING ALONE

97
00:04:33,418 --> 00:04:35,920
I didn't realize
there were houses like this in Korea.

98
00:04:35,921 --> 00:04:37,455
A NEW HOME

99
00:04:37,456 --> 00:04:38,623
WITH A COZY YARD

100
00:04:38,624 --> 00:04:40,158
This place is definitely dreamy.

101
00:04:44,429 --> 00:04:46,898
THE FINAL CHALLENGE BEFORE MOVING IN

102
00:04:46,899 --> 00:04:48,933
A TALL STAIRCASE

103
00:04:48,934 --> 00:04:50,168
This is going to be rough.

104
00:04:52,838 --> 00:04:55,941
YOU'VE GOT THIS, ASIA PRINCE

105
00:04:56,341 --> 00:04:57,342
GRUNTS

106
00:04:57,943 --> 00:04:59,210
GRUNTS

107
00:04:59,211 --> 00:05:02,014
IS THE GROAN PROPORTIONATE
TO HIS ADVANCED YEARS?

108
00:05:03,382 --> 00:05:05,617
FINALLY, 3 SECONDS BEFORE MOVING IN

109
00:05:06,151 --> 00:05:08,053
HEART POUNDING

110
00:05:10,555 --> 00:05:11,957
HESITANT

111
00:05:15,327 --> 00:05:18,430
IS SOMEONE HOME?

112
00:05:19,698 --> 00:05:23,368
CAUTIOUSLY ENTERING
THE STRANGE NEW HOME

113
00:05:30,642 --> 00:05:33,110
<i>What's this fancy scent?</i>

114
00:05:33,111 --> 00:05:34,279
WELCOME TO GUGI-DONG HOUSE

115
00:05:36,315 --> 00:05:40,585
CROSS THE QUIET HALLWAY

116
00:05:42,354 --> 00:05:43,355
GASPS

117
00:05:43,922 --> 00:05:45,924
EYES WIDE

118
00:05:48,126 --> 00:05:50,329
<i>I love it. It's so warm in here.</i>

119
00:05:51,430 --> 00:05:53,832
THEIR JOURNEY TOGETHER
WILL BEGIN HERE

120
00:05:56,335 --> 00:05:58,669
NEXT TO THE LIVING ROOM
IS THE DINING ROOM

121
00:05:58,670 --> 00:06:01,372
<i>The dining table...
Hey, so this leads to the kitchen.</i>

122
00:06:01,373 --> 00:06:03,742
A BIG DINING TABLE,
RARE IN A PLACE FOR ONE

123
00:06:04,009 --> 00:06:05,410
Hey, here's the kitchen.

124
00:06:06,979 --> 00:06:08,947
THE MOST ENTHUSIASTIC REACTION YET

125
00:06:14,019 --> 00:06:15,954
All the utensils are here.

126
00:06:16,788 --> 00:06:20,091
A steamer, a gas stove,
an induction stove...

127
00:06:20,092 --> 00:06:23,394
Oh, look at these pots.
A rice cooker. A kitchenette.

128
00:06:23,395 --> 00:06:25,096
It's empty.

129
00:06:25,097 --> 00:06:27,199
Sweet. We've got a bunch of jams.

130
00:06:27,599 --> 00:06:31,536
<i>This place is full of things I love.</i>

131
00:06:32,504 --> 00:06:35,306
<i>I can't wait to meet new friends</i>

132
00:06:35,307 --> 00:06:38,209
<i>to share this chapter of my life.</i>

133
00:06:38,210 --> 00:06:40,544
<i>I'm filled with high hopes.</i>

134
00:06:40,545 --> 00:06:41,713
NERVOUS

135
00:06:42,147 --> 00:06:44,349
WHEN WILL HIS HOUSEMATES ARRIVE?

136
00:06:47,119 --> 00:06:48,619
What's with this fancy mansion?

137
00:06:48,620 --> 00:06:49,987
THE SECOND TENANT HAS ARRIVED

138
00:06:49,988 --> 00:06:51,690
This must be a fancy neighborhood.

139
00:06:55,093 --> 00:06:56,327
This is so grand.

140
00:06:56,328 --> 00:06:58,397
JANG DO-YEON
SOLO DWELLER OF 14 YEARS

141
00:07:00,465 --> 00:07:04,168
<i>Hello, I'm Jang Do-yeon.
I've lived alone for 14 years now.</i>

142
00:07:04,169 --> 00:07:05,269
Just recently...

143
00:07:05,270 --> 00:07:06,804
Wait, was it in last year?

144
00:07:06,805 --> 00:07:09,373
I was feeling really sick.

145
00:07:09,374 --> 00:07:12,376
If only someone had asked me
how I was doing

146
00:07:12,377 --> 00:07:13,844
I could've told them I was ill.

147
00:07:13,845 --> 00:07:17,014
But no one asked me,
so I had no one to whine to.

148
00:07:17,015 --> 00:07:18,683
If only

149
00:07:19,184 --> 00:07:20,718
one person had checked on me...

150
00:07:20,719 --> 00:07:22,386
Even if they had asked
something silly

151
00:07:22,387 --> 00:07:25,990
I could've told them
I had come down with a cold.

152
00:07:25,991 --> 00:07:28,426
You only need that one person.

153
00:07:28,427 --> 00:07:31,262
There's a huge difference
when nobody knows how you're doing.

154
00:07:31,263 --> 00:07:33,998
It's awful to be alone
when you're not feeling well.

155
00:07:33,999 --> 00:07:38,803
Maybe it's just me,
but time feels like it's flying by.

156
00:07:38,804 --> 00:07:41,405
I thought that if I stuck to my ways

157
00:07:41,406 --> 00:07:43,542
I would forever be alone.

158
00:07:43,842 --> 00:07:45,709
So I decided to live with others.

159
00:07:45,710 --> 00:07:47,645
If it doesn't work out

160
00:07:47,646 --> 00:07:50,515
I can keep living alone.

161
00:07:51,383 --> 00:07:52,817
If it works for me

162
00:07:52,818 --> 00:07:56,087
I'll take it as proof
I can adapt to a new lifestyle

163
00:07:56,088 --> 00:07:57,922
and find joy in shared living.

164
00:07:57,923 --> 00:07:59,056
In a way

165
00:07:59,057 --> 00:08:02,194
this is a big challenge for me.

166
00:08:03,862 --> 00:08:05,397
Hello.

167
00:08:06,264 --> 00:08:07,898
AN ELDERLY NEIGHBOR PASSING BY

168
00:08:07,899 --> 00:08:09,366
Hello.

169
00:08:09,367 --> 00:08:10,634
- What are you doing here?
- Sorry?

170
00:08:10,635 --> 00:08:11,969
- I'm moving in.
- What?

171
00:08:11,970 --> 00:08:13,537
I'm moving in today.

172
00:08:13,538 --> 00:08:15,473
- Moving in.
- You're clocking in?

173
00:08:15,474 --> 00:08:16,974
- No, I'm moving in.
- I see.

174
00:08:16,975 --> 00:08:18,476
I live just over there.

175
00:08:18,477 --> 00:08:20,611
Really? We'll be neighbors, then.

176
00:08:20,612 --> 00:08:22,346
Neighbors?

177
00:08:22,347 --> 00:08:23,914
Hope we can be good neighbors.

178
00:08:23,915 --> 00:08:26,250
Who's the current renter?

179
00:08:26,251 --> 00:08:27,618
- My mentor?
- Yes.

180
00:08:27,619 --> 00:08:29,653
- Well...
- Is it still the Qataris?

181
00:08:29,654 --> 00:08:33,124
- A Qatari officer used to stay here.
- A Qatari officer?

182
00:08:33,125 --> 00:08:35,359
- An official from Qatar?
- Yes.

183
00:08:35,360 --> 00:08:38,362
- They used to live here?
- Yes, they used to live here.

184
00:08:38,363 --> 00:08:42,566
After they left,
Russian diplomats moved in.

185
00:08:42,567 --> 00:08:43,634
- Oh, really?
- Yes.

186
00:08:43,635 --> 00:08:45,603
Sounds like a fine neighborhood.

187
00:08:45,604 --> 00:08:46,837
Goodbye, sir.

188
00:08:46,838 --> 00:08:48,273
SEE YOU AROUND

189
00:08:49,674 --> 00:08:52,110
What on earth?
Isn't this where the chairman lives?

190
00:08:53,311 --> 00:08:55,313
I've never lived
in a place like this.

191
00:08:57,816 --> 00:09:01,652
I guess I'll have to leave early
to get to work on time.

192
00:09:01,653 --> 00:09:02,821
TENANT 2,
ALREADY WORRIED ABOUT COMMUTING

193
00:09:03,622 --> 00:09:04,789
How far do I have to go?

194
00:09:09,394 --> 00:09:10,462
Someone's here.

195
00:09:12,797 --> 00:09:14,131
Someone's arrived.

196
00:09:14,132 --> 00:09:15,266
Who is it?

197
00:09:15,267 --> 00:09:16,334
NERVOUS BUT EXCITED

198
00:09:17,335 --> 00:09:19,104
LATCHING ON TO THE WALL

199
00:09:19,671 --> 00:09:21,006
I hope no one is inside.

200
00:09:24,409 --> 00:09:26,443
COMPLETE SILENCE

201
00:09:26,444 --> 00:09:27,579
Is no one home?

202
00:09:29,281 --> 00:09:31,383
OF COURSE NOT

203
00:09:32,684 --> 00:09:34,920
AN UNEXPECTED EYE CONTACT

204
00:09:36,988 --> 00:09:38,890
- Hello.
- Hello.

205
00:09:39,824 --> 00:09:40,958
MASKING AWKWARDNESS WITH LAUGHTER

206
00:09:40,959 --> 00:09:42,726
- So you're here.
- Yes.

207
00:09:42,727 --> 00:09:43,961
I arrived first.

208
00:09:43,962 --> 00:09:45,963
- Really? So you're alone?
- Yes.

209
00:09:45,964 --> 00:09:48,532
I got here five minutes ago.
I honestly don't know much.

210
00:09:48,533 --> 00:09:50,268
- I'll carry it for you.
- Thank you.

211
00:09:50,835 --> 00:09:53,871
SILENCE FALLS
AFTER GREETINGS ARE EXCHANGED

212
00:09:53,872 --> 00:09:55,372
That's a neat pair of joggers.

213
00:09:55,373 --> 00:09:57,042
Yes, I chose a trendy pair.

214
00:09:58,009 --> 00:09:59,711
We have you, Do-yeon.

215
00:10:00,579 --> 00:10:02,914
BOTH HAVE LIVED ALONE FOR 14 YEARS

216
00:10:03,582 --> 00:10:04,648
This place is huge.

217
00:10:04,649 --> 00:10:05,716
Please take a look around.

218
00:10:05,717 --> 00:10:07,585
Not that I've been here long enough.

219
00:10:07,586 --> 00:10:08,852
GAZING AT A FARAWAY SPOT

220
00:10:08,853 --> 00:10:11,422
Wow, this looks like a place
you only see on TV.

221
00:10:11,423 --> 00:10:12,757
Well, it will go on air soon.

222
00:10:13,725 --> 00:10:16,994
UNSURE OF WHAT TO DO OR WHERE TO GO

223
00:10:16,995 --> 00:10:18,562
DEEP IN THOUGHT

224
00:10:18,563 --> 00:10:20,031
You know what?

225
00:10:20,932 --> 00:10:23,602
If someone snuck in here,
<i>Parasite</i> style

226
00:10:24,236 --> 00:10:25,503
no one will know.

227
00:10:29,941 --> 00:10:33,311
IT'S SO PAINFULLY AWKWARD

228
00:10:34,279 --> 00:10:37,449
HOW ARE THEY GOING TO LIVE TOGETHER?

229
00:10:38,550 --> 00:10:39,883
I'm surprisingly not good

230
00:10:39,884 --> 00:10:41,552
- around strangers.
- Really?

231
00:10:41,553 --> 00:10:44,822
- I may not seem like it, but...
- Are you putting on extra effort?

232
00:10:44,823 --> 00:10:46,390
I'm doing my best here.

233
00:10:46,391 --> 00:10:48,193
Would you like some alcohol?

234
00:10:51,096 --> 00:10:52,763
There's nothing in the refrigerator.

235
00:10:52,764 --> 00:10:54,064
- Nothing at all?
- None.

236
00:10:54,065 --> 00:10:55,867
What a shame.

237
00:10:58,970 --> 00:11:00,504
DO-YEON IS A SEASONED HOST

238
00:11:00,505 --> 00:11:01,972
SIGH

239
00:11:01,973 --> 00:11:04,708
BUT MEETING NEW HOUSEMATE
ISN'T EASY FOR HER EITHER

240
00:11:04,709 --> 00:11:06,011
HOPEFULLY, OTHERS WILL ARRIVE SOON

241
00:11:08,280 --> 00:11:10,015
Please go ahead.

242
00:11:10,849 --> 00:11:11,850
After you.

243
00:11:13,451 --> 00:11:14,686
A DEEP BOW

244
00:11:15,320 --> 00:11:16,788
You can pass.

245
00:11:17,656 --> 00:11:18,722
Please go on.

246
00:11:18,723 --> 00:11:20,759
AN ESPECIALLY POLITE MIDDLE-AGED MAN

247
00:11:21,693 --> 00:11:24,329
CHOI DANIEL
SOLO DWELLER OF 20 YEARS

248
00:11:25,597 --> 00:11:26,730
CHOI DANIEL
GLASSES HOTTIE, DATING SHOW FAN

249
00:11:26,731 --> 00:11:27,798
<i>Hello.</i>

250
00:11:27,799 --> 00:11:30,401
<i>I've been living alone for 20 years.</i>

251
00:11:30,402 --> 00:11:31,802
<i>My name is Choi Daniel.</i>

252
00:11:31,803 --> 00:11:33,570
WHY DID YOU JOIN THE SHOW?

253
00:11:33,571 --> 00:11:36,373
I imagined it would be like a show
where everyone pairs up.

254
00:11:36,374 --> 00:11:37,509
You never know, right?

255
00:11:37,909 --> 00:11:39,978
Three men and three women.

256
00:11:42,781 --> 00:11:45,016
JUST THE THOUGHT IS ENOUGH
TO MAKE HIS HEART FLUTTER

257
00:11:46,284 --> 00:11:47,452
The place is huge.

258
00:11:49,487 --> 00:11:50,688
Are we sure this is a house?

259
00:11:50,689 --> 00:11:52,324
Is this part of the mansion?

260
00:11:52,724 --> 00:11:53,892
Is this just a road?

261
00:11:55,960 --> 00:11:57,562
There's a hill on the property.

262
00:11:58,697 --> 00:11:59,763
What on earth?

263
00:11:59,764 --> 00:12:00,898
AN UNFILTERED TENANT IS HERE

264
00:12:00,899 --> 00:12:02,767
Is it part of the estate?

265
00:12:03,735 --> 00:12:05,170
This is wild.

266
00:12:07,939 --> 00:12:09,073
What's this?

267
00:12:09,074 --> 00:12:10,240
RATTLING ON

268
00:12:10,241 --> 00:12:11,376
Is this it?

269
00:12:13,278 --> 00:12:15,280
This is incredible.

270
00:12:16,414 --> 00:12:18,583
It's giving <i>Heart Signal.</i>

271
00:12:20,418 --> 00:12:21,652
WOBBLING

272
00:12:21,653 --> 00:12:23,387
SHALLOW BREATHS

273
00:12:23,388 --> 00:12:25,757
WHAT HAPPENED TO AIMING
FOR A DATING-SHOW-LIKE VIBE?

274
00:12:33,064 --> 00:12:34,833
Wow, this is amazing.

275
00:12:35,400 --> 00:12:36,735
What's this?

276
00:12:38,370 --> 00:12:40,938
TAKING A PEEK

277
00:12:40,939 --> 00:12:42,407
Here comes a funny guy.

278
00:12:43,775 --> 00:12:45,777
- Hello.
- What's going on?

279
00:12:46,478 --> 00:12:48,645
- Hello.
- What's going on?

280
00:12:48,646 --> 00:12:50,547
- Hi.
- Hello.

281
00:12:50,548 --> 00:12:52,149
- Hello.
- You were here.

282
00:12:52,150 --> 00:12:53,217
- It's a pleasure.
- Welcome.

283
00:12:53,218 --> 00:12:54,284
It's nice to meet you.

284
00:12:54,285 --> 00:12:56,487
They were peeking out
from behind the wall.

285
00:12:56,488 --> 00:12:58,722
It really hit me at that moment.

286
00:12:58,723 --> 00:13:01,326
No one's waiting to take a peek
when I get home.

287
00:13:01,860 --> 00:13:02,861
So...

288
00:13:04,529 --> 00:13:05,529
By the way...

289
00:13:05,530 --> 00:13:06,864
LOOKING AROUND

290
00:13:06,865 --> 00:13:09,333
I've only seen a place like this
on television.

291
00:13:09,334 --> 00:13:10,667
- Television?
- Television...

292
00:13:10,668 --> 00:13:12,003
I meant TV.

293
00:13:12,670 --> 00:13:14,071
It's like a sitcom.

294
00:13:14,072 --> 00:13:16,807
- Hey, it's like an old sitcom.
- Exactly.

295
00:13:16,808 --> 00:13:19,176
- Really?
- Were you thinking of another show?

296
00:13:19,177 --> 00:13:20,345
- I...
- Tell us the name.

297
00:13:21,346 --> 00:13:23,080
I was thinking of <i>Heart Signal.</i>

298
00:13:23,081 --> 00:13:25,015
- But the guys...
- Something like a dating show.

299
00:13:25,016 --> 00:13:27,217
The whole vibe is just...

300
00:13:27,218 --> 00:13:28,619
I like those kinds of shows.

301
00:13:28,620 --> 00:13:29,686
- Do you follow them?
- Yes.

302
00:13:29,687 --> 00:13:32,022
- So you're a fan of dating shows.
- My favorite is <i>Heart Signal.</i>

303
00:13:32,023 --> 00:13:33,657
- I've watched every episode.
- HS.

304
00:13:33,658 --> 00:13:34,792
Yes, HS.

305
00:13:34,793 --> 00:13:38,563
This is how people wait for others

306
00:13:38,897 --> 00:13:40,898
then live together for a while.

307
00:13:40,899 --> 00:13:42,634
That's the energy I'm getting.
The house...

308
00:13:43,601 --> 00:13:44,602
It's so grand.

309
00:13:47,505 --> 00:13:49,374
OUT OF TOPICS

310
00:13:50,675 --> 00:13:54,012
CAN ANYONE PLEASE SAY SOMETHING?

311
00:13:54,512 --> 00:13:55,647
That was amusing.

312
00:13:58,349 --> 00:13:59,883
I find it hilarious

313
00:13:59,884 --> 00:14:01,685
that things are this awkward

314
00:14:01,686 --> 00:14:03,053
when we're supposed to live together.

315
00:14:03,054 --> 00:14:04,121
I'm sure it will get better.

316
00:14:04,122 --> 00:14:06,857
- Of course, we'll get closer.
- That's bound to happen.

317
00:14:06,858 --> 00:14:08,759
- It's just...
- Look how demure I'm being.

318
00:14:08,760 --> 00:14:11,028
I actually moved in closer
because my initial seat was too far.

319
00:14:11,029 --> 00:14:13,297
I even have my knees closed.

320
00:14:13,298 --> 00:14:14,499
When we leave this place

321
00:14:15,400 --> 00:14:17,669
we'll just walk out as strangers

322
00:14:17,969 --> 00:14:20,704
- I'm curious what will happen.
- or go out for a big meal together.

323
00:14:20,705 --> 00:14:22,707
- It's one of these two.
- So curious. I agree.

324
00:14:27,145 --> 00:14:30,081
A LUXURY SEDAN PULLS UP

325
00:14:31,783 --> 00:14:34,052
TO DROP OFF A CHIC BEAUTY

326
00:14:37,055 --> 00:14:39,057
LEE DA-HEE
SOLO DWELLER OF 7 YEARS

327
00:14:40,425 --> 00:14:42,326
LEE DA-HEE
MS. CHEERFUL, QUIRKY GIRL CHARM

328
00:14:42,327 --> 00:14:44,595
<i>Hello. I've been living alone
for seven years now.</i>

329
00:14:44,596 --> 00:14:47,831
My parents and I live
on a different floors.

330
00:14:47,832 --> 00:14:49,100
My name is Lee Da-hee.

331
00:14:49,901 --> 00:14:50,901
WHY DID YOU JOIN THE SHOW?

332
00:14:50,902 --> 00:14:53,738
Marriage isn't exactly
the answer for everyone.

333
00:14:54,072 --> 00:14:56,039
I signed up for the show because...

334
00:14:56,040 --> 00:14:58,976
Honestly, I'm happy
with my current lifestyle.

335
00:14:58,977 --> 00:15:01,846
I'm doing great,
and I'm very satisfied.

336
00:15:02,280 --> 00:15:04,047
But once I've gotten older

337
00:15:04,048 --> 00:15:05,682
and my parents...

338
00:15:05,683 --> 00:15:08,318
Well, they would pass away one day.

339
00:15:08,319 --> 00:15:11,622
Then, I would be completely alone.

340
00:15:11,623 --> 00:15:14,124
That prospect frightens me, actually.

341
00:15:14,125 --> 00:15:16,093
I wonder,
"Will I be okay living alone?"

342
00:15:16,094 --> 00:15:17,495
"Won't I get lonely?"

343
00:15:17,996 --> 00:15:19,330
After all the musings

344
00:15:19,531 --> 00:15:22,599
I wanted to see if I could have
a different form of a family.

345
00:15:22,600 --> 00:15:24,235
That thought hit me.

346
00:15:25,436 --> 00:15:27,171
I'm so nervous.

347
00:15:28,606 --> 00:15:30,007
I'm moving in.

348
00:15:30,008 --> 00:15:31,608
This is it. I'm really moving in now.

349
00:15:31,609 --> 00:15:32,976
Oh, my.

350
00:15:32,977 --> 00:15:34,745
How will I manage?

351
00:15:34,746 --> 00:15:36,947
RUMBLING SOUND?

352
00:15:36,948 --> 00:15:39,149
I'm really moving in now. Oh, my.

353
00:15:39,150 --> 00:15:40,885
How will I manage?

354
00:15:41,553 --> 00:15:47,258
WATCH ME GO

355
00:15:51,796 --> 00:15:54,064
RACING AFTER

356
00:15:54,065 --> 00:15:56,100
STAFF MEMBERS ARE STARTLED AS WELL

357
00:15:57,302 --> 00:15:58,435
SO FAR AWAY

358
00:15:58,436 --> 00:15:59,771
Hello.

359
00:16:00,338 --> 00:16:01,606
Oh, no.

360
00:16:02,040 --> 00:16:03,040
I'm out of breath.

361
00:16:03,041 --> 00:16:06,376
WHAT A ROCKY START

362
00:16:06,377 --> 00:16:07,579
Hang on.

363
00:16:07,845 --> 00:16:10,814
TOO NERVOUS TO CRACK A SMILE

364
00:16:10,815 --> 00:16:13,417
SHE NEEDS SOME TIME TO REGROUP
MENTALLY AND PHYSICALLY

365
00:16:13,418 --> 00:16:14,752
ALMOST FALLING OVER

366
00:16:21,092 --> 00:16:24,596
FINALLY REACHED HER NEW HOME
AFTER A STRING OF MISHAPS

367
00:16:26,598 --> 00:16:29,000
MULTIPLE SUITCASES

368
00:16:35,306 --> 00:16:38,409
WE... WELCOME YOU

369
00:16:39,377 --> 00:16:42,714
A NEW NORM FOR THE WELCOMING PARTY
HAS BEEN ESTABLISHED

370
00:16:44,449 --> 00:16:45,749
SNICKERS

371
00:16:45,750 --> 00:16:46,817
Not yet.

372
00:16:46,818 --> 00:16:47,884
HOOKED

373
00:16:47,885 --> 00:16:50,120
- Looks like she'd need some help.
- Let's go help.

374
00:16:50,121 --> 00:16:51,789
- Shall we?
- All right, then.

375
00:16:52,357 --> 00:16:54,091
- Hello.
- Hello.

376
00:16:54,092 --> 00:16:55,993
- Hi.
- Nice to meet you.

377
00:16:55,994 --> 00:16:57,894
- You've brought quite a bit.
- Who do we have here?

378
00:16:57,895 --> 00:16:59,764
How have you been?

379
00:17:00,164 --> 00:17:01,164
Daniel.

380
00:17:01,165 --> 00:17:03,133
- How come you brought so much stuff?
- That's heavy.

381
00:17:03,134 --> 00:17:04,368
- I'll carry that.
- No, I'll do it.

382
00:17:04,369 --> 00:17:06,303
- This is yours as well, right?
- That's right.

383
00:17:06,304 --> 00:17:07,571
What's that?

384
00:17:07,572 --> 00:17:08,639
A chamber pot?

385
00:17:08,640 --> 00:17:10,340
How could you even suggest that?

386
00:17:10,341 --> 00:17:11,875
- A chamber pot?
- A seat of sorts.

387
00:17:11,876 --> 00:17:13,143
Can it be a bidet?

388
00:17:13,144 --> 00:17:15,113
- Oh, no. I'll do it.
- Okay.

389
00:17:15,346 --> 00:17:16,813
HEAD BUMP

390
00:17:16,814 --> 00:17:18,115
I'm so sorry.

391
00:17:18,116 --> 00:17:20,283
I just wanted to help.

392
00:17:20,284 --> 00:17:21,351
Goodness.

393
00:17:21,352 --> 00:17:23,053
ADDITIONAL HOUSEMATES
COME WITH MORE CHAOS

394
00:17:23,054 --> 00:17:24,121
What's this?

395
00:17:24,122 --> 00:17:26,591
- Is it a humidifier?
- Is that what it is?

396
00:17:26,858 --> 00:17:28,091
I thought it was a bidet.

397
00:17:28,092 --> 00:17:29,894
- I'm sorry about that.
- A chamber pot, really?

398
00:17:30,261 --> 00:17:32,129
It was all that came to mind.

399
00:17:32,130 --> 00:17:33,196
DA-HEE'S FAVORITE ITEM
HUMIDIFIER

400
00:17:33,197 --> 00:17:34,364
- Take a seat.
- So...

401
00:17:34,365 --> 00:17:36,701
- We have four people so far?
- Yes.

402
00:17:37,769 --> 00:17:38,935
- Have you been well?
- What?

403
00:17:38,936 --> 00:17:40,304
It's been ages.

404
00:17:41,105 --> 00:17:42,640
SO POLITE

405
00:17:43,041 --> 00:17:45,208
- What's with your hands?
- This place...

406
00:17:45,209 --> 00:17:46,576
AWKWARD REUNION BETWEEN OLD FRIENDS

407
00:17:46,577 --> 00:17:50,048
AND HERE'S ANOTHER PERSON

408
00:17:50,515 --> 00:17:51,515
TIDYING UP

409
00:17:51,516 --> 00:17:52,616
This place makes you well-mannered.

410
00:17:52,617 --> 00:17:54,218
- Take a seat.
- Please take a seat.

411
00:17:54,552 --> 00:17:55,619
- Right here.
- What's wrong?

412
00:17:55,620 --> 00:17:56,687
- This way.
- It's just...

413
00:17:56,688 --> 00:17:58,856
you looked super awkward
when you put up the blanket.

414
00:17:59,290 --> 00:18:00,323
ROAR OF LAUGHTER

415
00:18:00,324 --> 00:18:01,391
What blanket?

416
00:18:01,392 --> 00:18:03,194
You didn't have to fold it so neatly.

417
00:18:03,761 --> 00:18:04,761
Whatever.

418
00:18:04,762 --> 00:18:06,997
We've been talking
about having housemates.

419
00:18:06,998 --> 00:18:08,065
A QUICK CHANGE OF SUBJECT

420
00:18:08,066 --> 00:18:09,667
What's it like?

421
00:18:10,134 --> 00:18:12,136
I haven't tried it yet,
so I wouldn't know.

422
00:18:12,937 --> 00:18:13,938
True that.

423
00:18:14,872 --> 00:18:16,307
I haven't had a housemate yet.

424
00:18:16,741 --> 00:18:17,841
Honestly

425
00:18:17,842 --> 00:18:19,476
I haven't lived with anyone
as an adult.

426
00:18:19,477 --> 00:18:21,946
Come on, I wasn't trying to pry.

427
00:18:22,980 --> 00:18:23,980
It's just...

428
00:18:23,981 --> 00:18:26,083
- So you've never had a housemate
- Right.

429
00:18:26,084 --> 00:18:27,385
- as an adult.
- Yes, exactly.

430
00:18:27,785 --> 00:18:29,352
So, no human companion so far.

431
00:18:29,353 --> 00:18:30,488
WASN'T THAT THE TOPIC?

432
00:18:32,056 --> 00:18:34,659
This area is so lovely.

433
00:18:38,496 --> 00:18:41,499
ANOTHER TENANT WITH
AN UNUSUAL AMOUNT OF BELONGINGS

434
00:18:45,837 --> 00:18:47,270
KYUNG SOO-JIN
SOLO DWELLER OF 14 YEARS

435
00:18:47,271 --> 00:18:48,538
<i>Hello.</i>

436
00:18:48,539 --> 00:18:50,574
<i>I've been living alone for 14 years.</i>

437
00:18:50,575 --> 00:18:51,943
<i>My name is Kyung Soo-jin.</i>

438
00:18:52,477 --> 00:18:55,312
HOW OLD ARE YOU?

439
00:18:55,313 --> 00:18:57,447
PLAGUED BY A SUDDEN HEADACHE

440
00:18:57,448 --> 00:18:59,417
I've long forgotten to keep count.

441
00:19:00,585 --> 00:19:01,752
I'm 39.

442
00:19:01,753 --> 00:19:03,186
Wait, this is making me tear up.

443
00:19:03,187 --> 00:19:04,655
I'm 39 years old.

444
00:19:05,456 --> 00:19:09,459
The 39-year-olds back in the day
used to be legit 39-year-olds

445
00:19:09,460 --> 00:19:11,128
but things have changed.

446
00:19:11,129 --> 00:19:13,196
These days,
we need to dock ten years.

447
00:19:13,197 --> 00:19:15,099
That makes me 29.

448
00:19:15,800 --> 00:19:18,535
EMBARRASSED

449
00:19:18,536 --> 00:19:19,603
WHY DID YOU JOIN THE SHOW?

450
00:19:19,604 --> 00:19:20,904
I'd like to get married

451
00:19:20,905 --> 00:19:22,140
and have kids.

452
00:19:22,507 --> 00:19:24,609
The thing is, I don't have a partner.

453
00:19:25,076 --> 00:19:28,179
After living alone for 14 years

454
00:19:29,113 --> 00:19:32,949
could I really adjust to living
with someone?

455
00:19:32,950 --> 00:19:35,318
I've joined the show
to find that out.

456
00:19:35,319 --> 00:19:37,321
I wonder if I could, though.

457
00:19:42,360 --> 00:19:43,694
This isn't right.

458
00:19:44,729 --> 00:19:45,830
Wait.

459
00:19:46,164 --> 00:19:47,398
There's a staircase?

460
00:19:48,633 --> 00:19:49,733
What do I do?

461
00:19:49,734 --> 00:19:53,037
A DAUNTING TASK
FOR ONE PERSON TO TAKE ON

462
00:19:53,838 --> 00:19:55,005
GROANS

463
00:19:55,006 --> 00:19:56,473
GASPS

464
00:19:56,474 --> 00:19:58,109
Sounds like someone's approaching.

465
00:20:01,212 --> 00:20:02,479
Hello.

466
00:20:02,480 --> 00:20:04,115
A WELCOMING SIGHT
OF A POSSIBLE HELPING HAND

467
00:20:05,950 --> 00:20:07,517
- Hello.
- Oh, hello.

468
00:20:07,518 --> 00:20:08,585
Hi.

469
00:20:08,586 --> 00:20:09,821
- Watch out.
- Just a second.

470
00:20:10,888 --> 00:20:11,888
Oh, hello.

471
00:20:11,889 --> 00:20:15,026
A DREAMY FACE WITH A FRAIL PHYSIQUE

472
00:20:16,427 --> 00:20:18,129
AHN JAE-HYEON
SOLO DWELLER OF 7 YEARS

473
00:20:19,664 --> 00:20:21,364
AHN JAE-HYEON
MR. SWEETGUY, GOOFBALL

474
00:20:21,365 --> 00:20:23,133
<i>Hi, I've been living alone
for seven years now.</i>

475
00:20:23,134 --> 00:20:24,802
<i>My name is Ahn Jae-hyeon.</i>

476
00:20:25,169 --> 00:20:26,469
Now that I'm older...

477
00:20:26,470 --> 00:20:27,604
WHY DID YOU JOIN THE SHOW?

478
00:20:27,605 --> 00:20:29,372
...I've realized that my daily life

479
00:20:29,373 --> 00:20:31,275
and social circles

480
00:20:31,909 --> 00:20:36,279
are growing smaller by the day.

481
00:20:36,280 --> 00:20:38,682
Before they got any narrower

482
00:20:38,683 --> 00:20:41,151
I would like to expand the zone

483
00:20:41,152 --> 00:20:45,723
I share with my friends bit by bit.

484
00:20:46,624 --> 00:20:48,225
<i>I'd love to make great memories, too.</i>

485
00:20:48,226 --> 00:20:49,593
- Oh, hello.
- Hi.

486
00:20:49,594 --> 00:20:52,263
STARTING WITH AWKWARD MEMORIES

487
00:20:53,297 --> 00:20:54,632
Do you need a hand?

488
00:20:55,366 --> 00:20:56,666
HE SEEMS MORE LOST THAN HER

489
00:20:56,667 --> 00:20:57,734
Your suitcases...

490
00:20:57,735 --> 00:20:59,803
- Hi, Soo-jin.
- Hello.

491
00:20:59,804 --> 00:21:01,438
Why don't I give you a hand?

492
00:21:01,439 --> 00:21:03,173
- Why don't I take this?
- You can grab the handle.

493
00:21:03,174 --> 00:21:04,374
- The handle?
- That should do it.

494
00:21:04,375 --> 00:21:05,977
- You sure? Really?
- I can carry this.

495
00:21:07,345 --> 00:21:08,346
I...

496
00:21:08,913 --> 00:21:10,448
Looks like you brought more than me.

497
00:21:11,082 --> 00:21:12,283
I did bring quite a lot.

498
00:21:12,884 --> 00:21:15,419
- There's this staircase.
- Really?

499
00:21:15,620 --> 00:21:16,953
I never considered
I'd run into one here.

500
00:21:16,954 --> 00:21:19,457
- Guys can handle this easily.
- All right.

501
00:21:19,857 --> 00:21:21,225
- This...
- I'll carry this first.

502
00:21:21,559 --> 00:21:22,760
GRUNTS

503
00:21:23,361 --> 00:21:24,362
SIGHS

504
00:21:26,631 --> 00:21:29,367
HIS BREATH GROWS RAGGED
AS HE CARRIES A SINGLE SUITCASE

505
00:21:30,902 --> 00:21:31,903
SIGHS

506
00:21:34,572 --> 00:21:35,606
Wait.

507
00:21:36,908 --> 00:21:40,176
BOTH HANDS ARE FULLY OCCUPIED

508
00:21:40,177 --> 00:21:42,113
What do I do? I'm tired already.

509
00:21:43,748 --> 00:21:45,916
- Why don't I take this?
- Great. Thanks.

510
00:21:45,917 --> 00:21:47,350
- I'll carry this.
- Are you able to carry both?

511
00:21:47,351 --> 00:21:48,818
- I can manage.
- You sure?

512
00:21:48,819 --> 00:21:49,886
Of course.

513
00:21:49,887 --> 00:21:51,122
Let's go.

514
00:21:52,657 --> 00:21:54,325
A SHARP INTAKE

515
00:21:55,927 --> 00:21:57,795
GRUNTS

516
00:21:58,696 --> 00:21:59,696
SIGHS

517
00:21:59,697 --> 00:22:02,600
HE CAN BARELY BREATHE PROPERLY

518
00:22:04,602 --> 00:22:05,703
Hey, someone's here.

519
00:22:06,003 --> 00:22:07,605
- Someone's at the door.
- Is there?

520
00:22:08,406 --> 00:22:09,673
It feels like small surprises.

521
00:22:09,674 --> 00:22:11,943
- Do you want to greet them first?
- No, go ahead.

522
00:22:14,111 --> 00:22:15,178
Is it a woman?

523
00:22:15,179 --> 00:22:16,646
Wait, that sounds like a guy.

524
00:22:16,647 --> 00:22:17,714
It's a woman.

525
00:22:17,715 --> 00:22:18,915
No, it's a guy.

526
00:22:18,916 --> 00:22:20,151
Gosh, all this stuff...

527
00:22:21,519 --> 00:22:22,653
Just a second.

528
00:22:23,387 --> 00:22:24,688
- What? They came together?
- Hello.

529
00:22:24,689 --> 00:22:26,691
- Hello.
- Hello.

530
00:22:27,091 --> 00:22:28,259
- Hi.
- Why did you come together?

531
00:22:29,193 --> 00:22:30,493
We met just outside.

532
00:22:30,494 --> 00:22:31,862
Hello.

533
00:22:32,296 --> 00:22:33,631
- Hello.
- Hello.

534
00:22:33,998 --> 00:22:35,732
- Greetings.
- Hello.

535
00:22:35,733 --> 00:22:38,869
- Hello, everybody.
- Hey, Jae-hyeon.

536
00:22:39,737 --> 00:22:41,104
<i>We're all set now.</i>

537
00:22:41,105 --> 00:22:43,440
ALL HOUSEMATES HAVE MOVED IN

538
00:22:43,441 --> 00:22:47,845
The vibe here is very <i>Love House.</i>

539
00:22:48,245 --> 00:22:49,245
THIS GUY IS STILL DAYDREAMING

540
00:22:49,246 --> 00:22:51,082
<i>Love House</i> but without romance.

541
00:22:52,683 --> 00:22:53,950
Welcome.

542
00:22:53,951 --> 00:22:55,553
LET'S LIGHTEN THE AIR
WITH AN APPLAUSE

543
00:22:57,588 --> 00:22:59,857
- How awkward, right?
- He's cheerful for sure.

544
00:23:00,124 --> 00:23:01,624
SMACKING HIS LIPS

545
00:23:01,625 --> 00:23:02,792
How have you been?

546
00:23:02,793 --> 00:23:03,894
HOW HAVE YOU BEEN?

547
00:23:04,295 --> 00:23:05,729
I've been well.

548
00:23:05,730 --> 00:23:06,830
I don't believe we've met.

549
00:23:06,831 --> 00:23:08,264
- You're right.
- It's nice to meet you.

550
00:23:08,265 --> 00:23:09,533
You have warm hands.

551
00:23:09,900 --> 00:23:11,401
It's been so long, hasn't it?

552
00:23:11,402 --> 00:23:12,570
OLD COLLEAGUES REUNITED

553
00:23:12,837 --> 00:23:14,170
- <i>The Beauty Inside,</i> right?
- Right.

554
00:23:14,171 --> 00:23:15,372
I see it now.

555
00:23:15,373 --> 00:23:17,108
You know almost everyone here.

556
00:23:18,075 --> 00:23:20,143
- It's my first time...
- We've never met before.

557
00:23:20,144 --> 00:23:21,277
She's right.

558
00:23:21,278 --> 00:23:23,680
How come you guys came here together?

559
00:23:23,681 --> 00:23:26,117
- We met right outside.
- So you came together from home?

560
00:23:26,884 --> 00:23:28,152
No, just from the gate here.

561
00:23:28,519 --> 00:23:30,721
- He's trying to be funny again.
- So that's his style.

562
00:23:31,222 --> 00:23:33,457
- I mean, isn't it curious?
- Let's all take a seat.

563
00:23:34,325 --> 00:23:35,659
INCHING AWAY

564
00:23:37,995 --> 00:23:39,029
What's going on?

565
00:23:39,030 --> 00:23:40,530
EXCUSE ME

566
00:23:40,531 --> 00:23:42,298
TRYING TO AVOID THE CENTER SEAT

567
00:23:42,299 --> 00:23:43,366
That's not it.

568
00:23:43,367 --> 00:23:44,802
The corner seat is cold.

569
00:23:45,202 --> 00:23:46,202
What do you even mean?

570
00:23:46,203 --> 00:23:48,205
Are you worried I would be cold?
I've got my warm jacket on.

571
00:23:48,572 --> 00:23:50,141
- That makes no sense.
- It's just...

572
00:23:50,641 --> 00:23:52,542
My jacket is the warmest here.

573
00:23:52,543 --> 00:23:55,678
THE TENANTS ALL SEEM A LITTLE QUIRKY

574
00:23:55,679 --> 00:23:57,515
When I came here
after washing my hands...

575
00:23:58,315 --> 00:24:01,484
Maybe it's the power of this place,
but it somehow felt like

576
00:24:01,485 --> 00:24:03,219
I was on a college retreat
from years ago.

577
00:24:03,220 --> 00:24:05,021
You certainly look most relaxed.

578
00:24:05,022 --> 00:24:06,489
- Really?
- I agree.

579
00:24:06,490 --> 00:24:08,325
You're like the class rep.

580
00:24:09,226 --> 00:24:10,260
This is our home now.

581
00:24:10,261 --> 00:24:12,128
- We can lounge around, right?
- Sure.

582
00:24:12,129 --> 00:24:13,864
I like taking it easy as well.

583
00:24:14,732 --> 00:24:15,933
Let's all relax.

584
00:24:16,934 --> 00:24:19,335
- But you're all stiff like this.
- I'm holding my hands together.

585
00:24:19,336 --> 00:24:21,505
Like someone meeting
their in-laws for the first time.

586
00:24:21,906 --> 00:24:23,673
- You're not so different from me.
- That's true.

587
00:24:23,674 --> 00:24:25,776
Maybe it's because I'm long-limbed.

588
00:24:26,944 --> 00:24:29,913
CAN THEY BECOME GOOD FRIENDS?

589
00:24:29,914 --> 00:24:32,349
MAYBE THEY HAVE GOTTEN TOO CLOSE?

590
00:24:33,184 --> 00:24:36,286
THINGS GET WILDER AS THEY GET CLOSER

591
00:24:36,287 --> 00:24:38,722
BUILDING A LIFE TOGETHER
WITH FRIENDS OF SIMILAR AGE

592
00:24:39,090 --> 00:24:40,791
- It's going off track! Turn it off!
- No.

593
00:24:41,225 --> 00:24:42,525
WEIRDOS

594
00:24:42,526 --> 00:24:44,495
MEET EVEN BIGGER ODDBALLS

595
00:24:44,795 --> 00:24:46,130
Are you not planning to get married?

596
00:24:47,231 --> 00:24:49,567
You're not leaving here
until you get married!

597
00:24:50,468 --> 00:24:52,903
YOU MIGHT NOT BE ABLE TO MOVE OUT,
BUT CONGRATULATIONS ON MOVING IN

598
00:24:53,904 --> 00:24:55,005
Shall we check these out?

599
00:24:55,639 --> 00:24:56,974
The sign-up cards.

600
00:24:58,843 --> 00:25:00,443
- From earlier?
- We filled the form earlier.

601
00:25:00,444 --> 00:25:02,379
- You get a set each.
- Take one each.

602
00:25:04,548 --> 00:25:05,616
May I ask

603
00:25:06,550 --> 00:25:07,651
how old you are?

604
00:25:08,219 --> 00:25:10,920
- I was born in 1987.
- We'd be similar in age.

605
00:25:10,921 --> 00:25:13,356
- You too, right?
- Yes, in the Year of Rabbit.

606
00:25:13,357 --> 00:25:15,426
- In 1987?
- Born in November.

607
00:25:16,193 --> 00:25:17,260
Same here.

608
00:25:17,261 --> 00:25:18,962
- All three of you were born in 1987?
- Yes.

609
00:25:18,963 --> 00:25:20,864
- The Year of Rabbit.
- So it seems.

610
00:25:20,865 --> 00:25:22,632
I was born in March 1985.

611
00:25:22,633 --> 00:25:23,800
- Same here.
- Really?

612
00:25:23,801 --> 00:25:25,201
Yes, I was born in March.

613
00:25:25,202 --> 00:25:27,604
I heard we're all similar in age.

614
00:25:27,605 --> 00:25:28,839
Well...

615
00:25:29,373 --> 00:25:32,041
I was born early in 1986,
the Year of the Tiger.

616
00:25:32,042 --> 00:25:34,478
Since I was born early in the year,
I started school early.

617
00:25:34,812 --> 00:25:36,580
That's an unnecessarily long story.

618
00:25:38,249 --> 00:25:39,816
- It's just...
- Just tell us the year.

619
00:25:39,817 --> 00:25:40,884
"Unnecessarily long."

620
00:25:40,885 --> 00:25:42,652
- Born in the Year of the Tiger...
- It's just...

621
00:25:42,653 --> 00:25:44,587
When were you born exactly?

622
00:25:44,588 --> 00:25:47,123
I started college in 2004.

623
00:25:47,124 --> 00:25:49,559
I started elementary school in 1992
and graduated in 1998.

624
00:25:49,560 --> 00:25:51,562
- His hand is trembling.
- Yes, so...

625
00:25:52,396 --> 00:25:55,198
So, Daniel.
You're born in the Year of the Tiger?

626
00:25:55,199 --> 00:25:58,369
- Technically, yes.
- That means we're different ages.

627
00:25:59,703 --> 00:26:01,805
In that case

628
00:26:02,439 --> 00:26:03,607
what should I do?

629
00:26:05,676 --> 00:26:07,610
- Do we kick him out?
- What do I do?

630
00:26:07,611 --> 00:26:08,978
- But...
- Kick him out?

631
00:26:08,979 --> 00:26:10,213
- Fine by me.
- We just got here.

632
00:26:10,214 --> 00:26:11,981
THE TENANTS ARE STRICT ABOUT AGE

633
00:26:11,982 --> 00:26:13,049
He hasn't unpacked yet.

634
00:26:13,050 --> 00:26:14,118
OUT BEFORE HE EVEN UNPACKS?

635
00:26:14,351 --> 00:26:16,419
It suddenly feels hot in here.

636
00:26:16,420 --> 00:26:18,054
- Let's say we're of the same age.
- Okay.

637
00:26:18,055 --> 00:26:20,391
- Three of us?
- We three are of the same age.

638
00:26:21,058 --> 00:26:23,827
It might feel a bit weird,
but should we talk casually?

639
00:26:24,128 --> 00:26:25,162
Should we?

640
00:26:25,763 --> 00:26:26,863
How about it?

641
00:26:26,864 --> 00:26:28,899
IT'S SO AWKWARD STILL

642
00:26:29,166 --> 00:26:30,700
- Love it.
- Okay.

643
00:26:30,701 --> 00:26:32,135
I think it's a good idea.

644
00:26:32,136 --> 00:26:33,770
- Let's try it, everyone.
- Good.

645
00:26:33,771 --> 00:26:34,837
Okay.

646
00:26:34,838 --> 00:26:37,006
<i>Are we reading
Do-yeon's card together?</i>

647
00:26:37,007 --> 00:26:39,343
<i>We'll review everyone's card,
not mine alone.</i>

648
00:26:39,610 --> 00:26:41,545
- You're an introvert?
- Yes.

649
00:26:42,179 --> 00:26:43,680
Your personality type is ISFJ.

650
00:26:43,681 --> 00:26:44,914
FJ, that's me.

651
00:26:44,915 --> 00:26:47,050
- You're an early riser.
- She's a planner.

652
00:26:47,051 --> 00:26:48,351
A DILIGENT EARLY RISER

653
00:26:48,352 --> 00:26:50,887
Da-hee sleeps for about 12 hours.

654
00:26:50,888 --> 00:26:51,988
A RIDE-OR-DIE LONG SLEEPER

655
00:26:51,989 --> 00:26:53,090
I'm jealous.

656
00:26:53,591 --> 00:26:55,458
We're rarely awake at the same time.

657
00:26:55,459 --> 00:26:58,361
- The hours don't overlap so much.
- I mean...

658
00:26:58,362 --> 00:27:00,830
She's sensitive to noise,
smell, cleanliness, and light.

659
00:27:00,831 --> 00:27:01,898
That covers everything.

660
00:27:01,899 --> 00:27:04,501
- No.
- She's sensitive to everything.

661
00:27:05,169 --> 00:27:06,803
I'm not exactly sensitive.

662
00:27:06,804 --> 00:27:09,839
I sleep better
with blackout curtains.

663
00:27:09,840 --> 00:27:12,243
If it's bright,
I wake up automatically.

664
00:27:13,344 --> 00:27:14,711
You're a good organizer?

665
00:27:14,712 --> 00:27:16,145
Are you good at cleaning?

666
00:27:16,146 --> 00:27:17,280
Overall organizing?

667
00:27:17,281 --> 00:27:18,449
Yes, I am.

668
00:27:19,116 --> 00:27:21,285
I'm helpless with organizing.

669
00:27:22,286 --> 00:27:23,554
When I'm cleaning at home...

670
00:27:23,787 --> 00:27:25,054
Suppose I cleared these to clean up.

671
00:27:25,055 --> 00:27:26,390
I'll put them back after.

672
00:27:26,991 --> 00:27:27,992
Just as they were.

673
00:27:28,592 --> 00:27:30,793
- I don't take out the bottles.
- We're pretty similar.

674
00:27:30,794 --> 00:27:32,829
- An order within disorder.
- Exactly.

675
00:27:32,830 --> 00:27:34,564
- Something only I know.
- For example

676
00:27:34,565 --> 00:27:36,766
keeping the remote close by
from where you'd be lying down.

677
00:27:36,767 --> 00:27:38,501
It should be hereabouts.

678
00:27:38,502 --> 00:27:40,670
I usually sit here,
and I get mad when it's not around.

679
00:27:40,671 --> 00:27:42,372
- That's it.
- I get what you mean.

680
00:27:42,373 --> 00:27:43,506
I get what you mean.

681
00:27:43,507 --> 00:27:45,709
DA-HEE FEELS A SUDDEN DREAD

682
00:27:45,976 --> 00:27:47,645
I've been letting it simmer.
It's time.

683
00:27:48,646 --> 00:27:50,681
SPILLING ALL OVER

684
00:27:52,249 --> 00:27:54,317
You know, Keun-suk.

685
00:27:54,318 --> 00:27:56,753
- You're pretty clumsy.
- You got me.

686
00:27:56,754 --> 00:27:58,054
- I let it all spill.
- Wherever you go

687
00:27:58,055 --> 00:28:00,390
you leave a trail
for someone else to clean up.

688
00:28:00,391 --> 00:28:02,525
ALL THE MESS KEUN-SUK MADE

689
00:28:02,526 --> 00:28:03,593
GAUGING HER MOOD

690
00:28:03,594 --> 00:28:05,329
I meant to throw them away next.

691
00:28:07,665 --> 00:28:08,932
I'm not trying to pressure you.

692
00:28:09,266 --> 00:28:10,667
Don't follow me around.

693
00:28:10,668 --> 00:28:12,101
Hey.

694
00:28:12,102 --> 00:28:13,436
I won't push you.

695
00:28:13,437 --> 00:28:17,274
A SHARP SCOLDING
YOU'D NEVER HEAR LIVING ALONE

696
00:28:17,641 --> 00:28:19,943
Why did you choose Hyeok
as your nickname?

697
00:28:20,344 --> 00:28:21,577
PREFERRED NICKNAME: HYEOK

698
00:28:21,578 --> 00:28:22,912
Seriously, it's rather random.

699
00:28:22,913 --> 00:28:24,480
- Why Hyeok of all names?
- Well...

700
00:28:24,481 --> 00:28:25,648
Let me share the background.

701
00:28:25,649 --> 00:28:29,553
I've always thought
"Daniel" sounded soft and gentle.

702
00:28:30,120 --> 00:28:33,090
- I've longed for a charismatic name.
- I get it know.

703
00:28:33,357 --> 00:28:35,258
- So you wanted Hyeok with a growl?
- Exactly.

704
00:28:35,259 --> 00:28:37,528
Like Min-hyeok or Jae-hyeok.

705
00:28:39,730 --> 00:28:41,230
"Having a filter."

706
00:28:41,231 --> 00:28:43,766
QUALITIES YOU LACK
HAVING A FILTER

707
00:28:43,767 --> 00:28:45,636
It seems he's aware on that.

708
00:28:46,203 --> 00:28:47,504
I know my faults.

709
00:28:48,272 --> 00:28:49,472
Can you give me an example?

710
00:28:49,473 --> 00:28:51,641
I haven't gotten that vibes from you.

711
00:28:51,642 --> 00:28:52,876
For example...

712
00:28:53,744 --> 00:28:55,078
Well, I...

713
00:28:55,079 --> 00:28:56,212
Do-yeon.

714
00:28:56,213 --> 00:29:00,249
I like how your lips
are slightly crooked.

715
00:29:00,250 --> 00:29:01,518
That's one example.

716
00:29:07,057 --> 00:29:08,524
I like how your lips
are slightly crooked.

717
00:29:08,525 --> 00:29:10,561
WHAT NOW?

718
00:29:10,894 --> 00:29:13,430
WHAT'S WRONG WITH HIM?

719
00:29:14,365 --> 00:29:15,665
The way I see it...

720
00:29:15,666 --> 00:29:17,633
Well, I...

721
00:29:17,634 --> 00:29:19,102
- That's fighting words.
- You know

722
00:29:19,103 --> 00:29:21,171
did someone ask
if I'm a decent fighter earlier?

723
00:29:22,172 --> 00:29:23,306
Oh, no.

724
00:29:23,307 --> 00:29:26,109
- That was just an example.
- That was funny.

725
00:29:26,110 --> 00:29:28,078
I honestly like that about you.

726
00:29:28,879 --> 00:29:31,047
It doesn't look weird to me at all.

727
00:29:31,048 --> 00:29:33,449
- But universally...
- I haven't heard that in a while.

728
00:29:33,450 --> 00:29:35,551
Only my fellow comedians
used to tease like that.

729
00:29:35,552 --> 00:29:36,686
It's been ages.

730
00:29:36,687 --> 00:29:39,122
- She's gotten beet red.
- I'm sorry.

731
00:29:39,123 --> 00:29:41,023
- It's actually hot, right?
- The heat...

732
00:29:41,024 --> 00:29:44,094
- I've kept my jacket on all along.
- It's hot in here.

733
00:29:44,628 --> 00:29:46,696
- Jeez, that hurts my ego.
- It's hot.

734
00:29:46,697 --> 00:29:48,831
- I don't want to get upset at that.
- Isn't it hot?

735
00:29:48,832 --> 00:29:51,568
- Should we turn down the heat a bit?
- It's kind of hot.

736
00:29:51,835 --> 00:29:54,437
I know I said that myself,
but that made me blush big time.

737
00:29:54,438 --> 00:29:56,839
- I meant to say...
- Let's talk without a filter, Hyeok.

738
00:29:56,840 --> 00:29:58,675
- I'll be just as candid with you.
- Hyeok.

739
00:29:59,510 --> 00:30:00,510
Hyeok.

740
00:30:00,511 --> 00:30:02,446
I'm getting used
to your way of talking.

741
00:30:02,980 --> 00:30:05,048
VACCINATED AGAINST HIS RANDOM JIBES

742
00:30:05,382 --> 00:30:06,416
- That's mine.
- Keun-chan.

743
00:30:06,417 --> 00:30:07,784
All right, Keun-chan.

744
00:30:07,785 --> 00:30:09,086
What's AP for?

745
00:30:09,453 --> 00:30:10,821
Oh, about that...

746
00:30:11,388 --> 00:30:12,789
It's embarrassing to say.

747
00:30:12,790 --> 00:30:14,824
- Is it a play on "papa"?
- Oh, no.

748
00:30:14,825 --> 00:30:16,025
No, it's a shorthand.

749
00:30:16,026 --> 00:30:17,861
- Is it an acronym?
- Yes.

750
00:30:18,595 --> 00:30:19,595
I know what it is.

751
00:30:19,596 --> 00:30:21,131
Asia Prince.

752
00:30:22,866 --> 00:30:23,934
My gosh.

753
00:30:24,635 --> 00:30:26,035
She got it right.

754
00:30:26,036 --> 00:30:28,237
I got the nickname when I was young.

755
00:30:28,238 --> 00:30:30,840
You know what, Keun-suk?

756
00:30:30,841 --> 00:30:32,508
- It still suits you perfectly.
- Sure.

757
00:30:32,509 --> 00:30:34,477
Everyone gets that.

758
00:30:34,478 --> 00:30:36,712
No one could say it doesn't suit you.

759
00:30:36,713 --> 00:30:39,616
- Please call me just AP.
- Okay, AP.

760
00:30:39,983 --> 00:30:42,285
"I've grown weary
of my lonesome days."

761
00:30:42,286 --> 00:30:44,822
That's the tricky part of life.

762
00:30:45,155 --> 00:30:49,092
I think everyone will agree.
I never felt lonesome in my twenties.

763
00:30:49,526 --> 00:30:53,262
Back then everything was new,
and I got to go out and have fun.

764
00:30:53,263 --> 00:30:55,632
- We were busy.
- That too.

765
00:30:55,899 --> 00:30:57,266
As you grow older

766
00:30:57,267 --> 00:30:59,268
you learn what it means
to be lonesome

767
00:30:59,269 --> 00:31:02,071
- in your daily life.
- That's so true.

768
00:31:02,072 --> 00:31:04,240
It's more than simply
being surrounded by silence.

769
00:31:04,241 --> 00:31:06,843
What's more, the silence
doesn't exactly soothe you.

770
00:31:06,844 --> 00:31:08,110
You feel like

771
00:31:08,111 --> 00:31:09,879
- taking a look around your place.
- Yeah.

772
00:31:09,880 --> 00:31:12,148
Even the air feels heavier, you know.

773
00:31:12,149 --> 00:31:13,349
That's lonesome for you.

774
00:31:13,350 --> 00:31:14,685
<i>When I return home...</i>

775
00:31:15,118 --> 00:31:17,688
Well, the lights are all off.
It's almost eerily quiet.

776
00:31:17,888 --> 00:31:21,625
When you suddenly crave
a company for dinner

777
00:31:22,426 --> 00:31:25,262
it's not so easy to find someone
who would be open to an invitation.

778
00:31:25,796 --> 00:31:28,599
That hits hard for me.

779
00:31:29,233 --> 00:31:30,233
From time to time

780
00:31:30,234 --> 00:31:34,171
I find myself thinking it's boring.

781
00:31:34,805 --> 00:31:37,373
When an interesting event
happens on my day at work...

782
00:31:37,374 --> 00:31:38,441
You know how it is.

783
00:31:38,442 --> 00:31:40,843
You could've had a very eventful day

784
00:31:40,844 --> 00:31:43,012
and would love nothing more
than to give a blow-by-blow account.

785
00:31:43,013 --> 00:31:45,681
Or you could've had a really bad day

786
00:31:45,682 --> 00:31:48,151
and would love to unwind
by sharing the day with someone.

787
00:31:48,819 --> 00:31:51,554
These days,
I find satisfaction through others.

788
00:31:51,555 --> 00:31:53,456
I'd watch a pack of friends

789
00:31:53,457 --> 00:31:57,493
going on a trip on TV shows or vlogs.

790
00:31:57,494 --> 00:31:59,229
Following other people's lives

791
00:32:00,163 --> 00:32:03,100
helped me overcome loneliness.

792
00:32:04,801 --> 00:32:08,337
I'd love to chat over some soju.

793
00:32:08,338 --> 00:32:10,239
"Let's go over our day together."

794
00:32:10,240 --> 00:32:12,108
"I'll tell you about my day first."

795
00:32:12,109 --> 00:32:15,646
We could just unwind
and relieve stress that way.

796
00:32:15,879 --> 00:32:20,449
I'd love to have someone
who could do that together.

797
00:32:20,450 --> 00:32:21,685
That's how I feel.

798
00:32:22,553 --> 00:32:26,290
AND NOW, THESE SIX PEOPLE

799
00:32:27,024 --> 00:32:28,391
HAVE HOUSEMATES

800
00:32:28,392 --> 00:32:30,593
Hey, AP. Have you eaten?

801
00:32:30,594 --> 00:32:31,661
TO SHARE THEIR DAY WITH

802
00:32:31,662 --> 00:32:33,530
I get "Hey, AP."
But what's with the next question?

803
00:32:34,197 --> 00:32:35,631
COULD THEY GET USED
TO LIVING TOGETHER?

804
00:32:35,632 --> 00:32:36,766
You only met briefly.

805
00:32:36,767 --> 00:32:38,735
- You can take it however you want.
- Oh, sure.

806
00:32:39,503 --> 00:32:40,670
You cook yourself?

807
00:32:40,671 --> 00:32:44,040
Oh, right. I know you're a good cook.
I've seen your YouTube videos.

808
00:32:44,041 --> 00:32:46,108
What are your go-to dishes?

809
00:32:46,109 --> 00:32:47,244
I use whatever's in the fridge.

810
00:32:49,046 --> 00:32:50,112
You can cook whatever?

811
00:32:50,113 --> 00:32:52,816
I can sort out a combo
and cook something up.

812
00:32:53,717 --> 00:32:55,084
HE PACKED SEASONING AND SAUCE FIRST

813
00:32:55,085 --> 00:32:57,386
<i>I brought seasoning
and sauce from home.</i>

814
00:32:57,387 --> 00:32:59,456
<i>This is amazing.</i>

815
00:33:00,257 --> 00:33:01,891
HE'S PASSIONATE ABOUT COOKING

816
00:33:01,892 --> 00:33:04,794
He's got a point.
Dinner time is a chance to connect.

817
00:33:04,795 --> 00:33:07,797
- We need good food for that.
- Of course.

818
00:33:07,798 --> 00:33:10,299
Actually, I prepared something

819
00:33:10,300 --> 00:33:13,036
since this is the first day
we meet each other.

820
00:33:13,804 --> 00:33:16,572
I wanted us to have
something fun and delicious

821
00:33:16,573 --> 00:33:18,040
so I ordered something just in case.

822
00:33:18,041 --> 00:33:19,508
Really? What is it?

823
00:33:19,509 --> 00:33:21,844
I thought it'd be nice
to have seafood together

824
00:33:21,845 --> 00:33:23,312
- so I placed an order.
- I'd love that.

825
00:33:23,313 --> 00:33:25,448
Really? Goodness.

826
00:33:25,449 --> 00:33:26,850
I'm not a seafood guy.

827
00:33:27,584 --> 00:33:28,618
What do we do?

828
00:33:28,619 --> 00:33:30,988
THERE HE GOES AGAIN

829
00:33:31,455 --> 00:33:33,056
THIS IS AWKWARD

830
00:33:33,724 --> 00:33:34,757
Well, I do enjoy it.

831
00:33:34,758 --> 00:33:36,793
I'm just not crazy about it,
but I don't hate it.

832
00:33:37,828 --> 00:33:39,296
I don't see the difference.

833
00:33:41,865 --> 00:33:44,200
We know you didn't mean to offend.

834
00:33:44,201 --> 00:33:45,368
I just phrased it wrong.

835
00:33:45,369 --> 00:33:47,303
He's not trying to be mean.
That's important.

836
00:33:47,304 --> 00:33:48,638
Let's work on

837
00:33:48,639 --> 00:33:50,941
overcoming our differences
during our time together.

838
00:33:51,408 --> 00:33:53,042
FROM HIS TASTE IN FOOD
TO HIS CHOICE OF WORDS

839
00:33:53,043 --> 00:33:54,177
THEY HAVE SO MUCH TO WORK ON

840
00:33:54,444 --> 00:33:56,445
Do you really go to bed at 4 a.m.?

841
00:33:56,446 --> 00:33:58,949
Yes, I have insomnia.

842
00:33:59,449 --> 00:34:00,750
- It's pretty bad.
- How come?

843
00:34:00,751 --> 00:34:02,352
That's why noises get to me.

844
00:34:03,620 --> 00:34:05,022
- So...
- I'd love to help.

845
00:34:05,322 --> 00:34:07,523
Falling asleep
is difficult for me as is.

846
00:34:07,524 --> 00:34:10,326
But if someone close by snores...

847
00:34:10,327 --> 00:34:11,394
THE BIGGEST THREAT TO SOO-JIN

848
00:34:11,395 --> 00:34:13,562
That's the worst-case scenario.

849
00:34:13,563 --> 00:34:15,899
SNORTS

850
00:34:16,600 --> 00:34:17,601
SIGHS

851
00:34:18,602 --> 00:34:21,037
IS HE TROUBLED?

852
00:34:21,038 --> 00:34:22,805
I'll have to stay up all night, then.

853
00:34:22,806 --> 00:34:25,941
It's absolutely the worst,
having trouble sleeping.

854
00:34:25,942 --> 00:34:28,444
- We'll have to be considerate.
- For sure.

855
00:34:28,445 --> 00:34:30,713
- I'd love to help somehow.
- Yes, same here.

856
00:34:30,714 --> 00:34:32,782
I really want to be of help
in any way.

857
00:34:32,783 --> 00:34:35,185
Did you know
about the guide at the back?

858
00:34:36,119 --> 00:34:39,990
Looks like it covers the rules
we have to keep while living here.

859
00:34:40,791 --> 00:34:42,992
<i>"All housemates should support
one another to complete a project</i>

860
00:34:42,993 --> 00:34:44,994
<i>that they hope to finish
before their next birthday</i>

861
00:34:44,995 --> 00:34:46,830
<i>- also known as House Squad Goal."
- That's nice.</i>

862
00:34:48,198 --> 00:34:50,801
THEY'RE NOT GROWING
A YEAR OLDER AS IS!

863
00:34:51,601 --> 00:34:57,340
STRANGE "HOUSE SQUAD GOAL"
OF THESE TRENDY ADULTS

864
00:34:58,608 --> 00:35:00,109
I'm the next-generation MC!

865
00:35:00,110 --> 00:35:05,916
LIFE DOESN'T HAVE SET ANSWERS!

866
00:35:07,084 --> 00:35:08,651
ONLY POSSIBLE THANKS TO FRIENDS

867
00:35:08,652 --> 00:35:11,922
WE'LL JUMP INTO OUR FORTIES
JUST AS WE ARE

868
00:35:13,023 --> 00:35:14,924
- Should we first choose a bedroom?
- Let's do that.

869
00:35:14,925 --> 00:35:16,492
- Let's take a tour first.
- Okay.

870
00:35:16,493 --> 00:35:17,560
I'm curious.

871
00:35:17,561 --> 00:35:18,627
What will they look like?

872
00:35:18,628 --> 00:35:20,896
LET'S START FROM THE ROOM
CLOSE TO THE COMMUNAL SPACE

873
00:35:20,897 --> 00:35:22,299
It's a bedroom.

874
00:35:22,966 --> 00:35:24,234
It was a bedroom!

875
00:35:25,502 --> 00:35:27,169
WARM SUNLIGHT ILLUMINATES
THE LIVELY ORANGE ROOM

876
00:35:27,170 --> 00:35:28,571
<i>This is the Orange Room.</i>

877
00:35:28,572 --> 00:35:30,173
<i>- You're right.
- It's for the captain.</i>

878
00:35:30,741 --> 00:35:32,108
<i>It's cozy in here.</i>

879
00:35:32,109 --> 00:35:33,876
<i>The room is all in orange.</i>

880
00:35:33,877 --> 00:35:35,377
<i>How neat.</i>

881
00:35:35,378 --> 00:35:36,546
<i>Look.</i>

882
00:35:37,447 --> 00:35:40,617
It might not be the place
for someone who likes it dark.

883
00:35:41,084 --> 00:35:42,485
- It doesn't cover the sunlight.
- Yes.

884
00:35:42,486 --> 00:35:43,886
- An early riser...
- All that sun.

885
00:35:43,887 --> 00:35:45,422
- They're not blackout ones.
- That's right.

886
00:35:46,056 --> 00:35:47,057
Can't we

887
00:35:47,924 --> 00:35:49,024
install them here?

888
00:35:49,025 --> 00:35:50,192
Whatever we do...

889
00:35:50,193 --> 00:35:52,061
- She wants to install them.
- What, yourself?

890
00:35:52,062 --> 00:35:54,663
We can get blackout curtains.

891
00:35:54,664 --> 00:35:56,365
I think she can handle it.

892
00:35:56,366 --> 00:35:57,734
Agreed.

893
00:35:58,769 --> 00:36:01,036
<i>At first glance,
the rooms are amazing.</i>

894
00:36:01,037 --> 00:36:02,171
CROSS THE LIVING ROOM

895
00:36:02,172 --> 00:36:04,373
<i>Hold on. What have we got here?</i>

896
00:36:04,374 --> 00:36:06,408
THERE IS ANOTHER BEDROOM
NEXT TO THE ENTRANCE

897
00:36:06,409 --> 00:36:08,211
<i>- Is this another room?
- It's a bedroom!</i>

898
00:36:08,979 --> 00:36:09,979
<i>All in red.</i>

899
00:36:09,980 --> 00:36:11,680
- This is the Red Room.
- So spacious.

900
00:36:11,681 --> 00:36:13,817
- This must be the master bedroom.
- It's huge.

901
00:36:15,085 --> 00:36:17,020
I love the dressing room.

902
00:36:17,587 --> 00:36:19,789
- It's giving the master bedroom.
- I see that.

903
00:36:19,790 --> 00:36:22,224
- What about the dressing room?
- This whole space for one person?

904
00:36:22,225 --> 00:36:25,028
- I don't think I can.
- Wow, look at that tub.

905
00:36:25,829 --> 00:36:26,997
There's another bedroom here.

906
00:36:29,099 --> 00:36:30,966
<i>So that's why a bathroom's here.</i>

907
00:36:30,967 --> 00:36:33,804
<i>- So they can share?
- So two people share one big space.</i>

908
00:36:34,604 --> 00:36:36,406
<i>- This is pretty cozy.
- It is.</i>

909
00:36:37,474 --> 00:36:40,042
This floor has three rooms in total.

910
00:36:40,043 --> 00:36:42,011
- Shall we go upstairs?
- Okay.

911
00:36:42,012 --> 00:36:44,280
<i>The house is a beauty.</i>

912
00:36:44,281 --> 00:36:46,549
<i>It's so nice here.</i>

913
00:36:46,550 --> 00:36:47,818
Why is it so warm here?

914
00:36:48,351 --> 00:36:49,752
Here's a bathroom.

915
00:36:49,753 --> 00:36:50,820
There's a tub here.

916
00:36:50,821 --> 00:36:51,921
<i>It's huge. Great.</i>

917
00:36:51,922 --> 00:36:53,690
THE SOLE BATHROOM ON THE 2ND FLOOR

918
00:36:53,990 --> 00:36:55,624
<i>Hey, there's another bedroom.</i>

919
00:36:55,625 --> 00:36:57,927
<i>- What? Right here?
- Here's another one.</i>

920
00:36:57,928 --> 00:36:59,495
- There's a bedroom here.
- What?

921
00:36:59,496 --> 00:37:01,764
Suppose you stay here.

922
00:37:01,765 --> 00:37:04,533
- All green.
- If someone's in the bathroom...

923
00:37:04,534 --> 00:37:05,835
What? There's a bedroom here?

924
00:37:05,836 --> 00:37:07,503
They'll need to coordinate.

925
00:37:07,504 --> 00:37:08,904
Like, "Can I go out?"

926
00:37:08,905 --> 00:37:10,706
- Do-yeon, look here.
- Hold on.

927
00:37:10,707 --> 00:37:11,942
- Is it a room?
- But...

928
00:37:12,542 --> 00:37:13,776
- It is a room!
- It's all connected.

929
00:37:13,777 --> 00:37:15,578
This room's occupant will have to go

930
00:37:15,579 --> 00:37:17,246
"Can I come out?"

931
00:37:17,247 --> 00:37:18,948
- They can only go if it's a yes.
- No door, right?

932
00:37:18,949 --> 00:37:20,783
- "Is it safe for me to go out?"
- "Can I come out?"

933
00:37:20,784 --> 00:37:22,384
- Hey, there's a door here.
- Really?

934
00:37:22,385 --> 00:37:24,421
So we each get a room.

935
00:37:25,589 --> 00:37:26,755
<i>This is the shabbiest here.</i>

936
00:37:26,756 --> 00:37:28,558
<i>It's the smallest one, too.</i>

937
00:37:28,925 --> 00:37:30,961
<i>- Meanwhile, this room... It's great.
- It's amazing.</i>

938
00:37:31,561 --> 00:37:33,963
<i>- What an awkward arrangement.
- I know.</i>

939
00:37:33,964 --> 00:37:35,665
<i>All connected to the bathroom.</i>

940
00:37:36,466 --> 00:37:38,801
<i>Let's gather at the table.</i>

941
00:37:38,802 --> 00:37:40,502
<i>Thankfully, we have six bedrooms.</i>

942
00:37:40,503 --> 00:37:42,439
<i>The tour has made my heart dance.</i>

943
00:37:43,139 --> 00:37:45,908
Why don't we take the rooms
on the second floor?

944
00:37:45,909 --> 00:37:47,443
- Guys can move in upstairs.
- Okay.

945
00:37:47,444 --> 00:37:49,845
You guys can share the rooms here.

946
00:37:49,846 --> 00:37:51,747
- Sounds good.
- Won't you mind the noise?

947
00:37:51,748 --> 00:37:53,917
- We get a room each, so...
- Suppose we go to the kitchen.

948
00:37:54,484 --> 00:37:55,484
It should be okay.

949
00:37:55,485 --> 00:37:57,219
Let's give Soo-jin the quietest room.

950
00:37:57,220 --> 00:37:59,788
- One room's tucked behind the other.
- They're connected.

951
00:37:59,789 --> 00:38:01,790
- Soo-jin should take that room.
- Oh, no.

952
00:38:01,791 --> 00:38:03,192
I don't mind at all.

953
00:38:03,193 --> 00:38:04,960
I think that's the better option.
It's nice and quiet.

954
00:38:04,961 --> 00:38:06,729
- Go on.
- You can rest better.

955
00:38:06,730 --> 00:38:08,097
- Take the private room.
- Okay.

956
00:38:08,098 --> 00:38:10,099
Soo-jin filled us in
on her concerns, right?

957
00:38:10,100 --> 00:38:11,867
- It'd be so funny if she slept well.
- Right?

958
00:38:11,868 --> 00:38:14,103
- That'd be lovely.
- Sleeping like a log.

959
00:38:14,104 --> 00:38:15,505
- That would be so funny.
- She snores, though.

960
00:38:17,407 --> 00:38:18,508
No one else can sleep, then.

961
00:38:18,875 --> 00:38:20,944
DO-YEON, RED ROOM
DA-HEE, YELLOW ROOM

962
00:38:22,245 --> 00:38:23,646
<i>There's a room accessible</i>

963
00:38:23,647 --> 00:38:26,215
<i>- only through the bathroom.
- Oh, right.</i>

964
00:38:26,216 --> 00:38:28,117
<i>The Green Room upstairs.</i>

965
00:38:28,118 --> 00:38:29,852
<i>That room drew the short straw.</i>

966
00:38:29,853 --> 00:38:30,920
<i>A weak link.</i>

967
00:38:30,921 --> 00:38:32,255
WHO WILL GET THE AWKWARD LITTLE NOOK?

968
00:38:44,410 --> 00:38:45,410
UNEASY FOR SOME REASON

969
00:38:45,411 --> 00:38:46,711
Jump.

970
00:38:46,712 --> 00:38:48,513
CONGRATS, YOU GET THE GREEN ROOM

971
00:38:48,514 --> 00:38:49,781
Jump.

972
00:38:49,782 --> 00:38:51,350
WINNER OF THE GHOST LEG IS JAE-HYEON

973
00:38:51,917 --> 00:38:53,918
GREEN ROOM'S OCCUPANT
DROPS TO THE FLOOR IN DESPAIR

974
00:38:53,919 --> 00:38:55,620
See? I knew this would happen.

975
00:38:55,621 --> 00:38:56,988
I knew it.

976
00:38:56,989 --> 00:38:59,591
- What was that listless "jump" for?
- Right?

977
00:39:00,392 --> 00:39:02,660
That order at the end
was so spiritless.

978
00:39:02,661 --> 00:39:03,728
"Jump."

979
00:39:03,729 --> 00:39:08,399
"FRIENDLY" MOCKERY FOLLOWS
INSTEAD OF WORDS OF COMFORT

980
00:39:08,400 --> 00:39:10,101
<i>If only he hadn't said that.</i>

981
00:39:10,102 --> 00:39:11,169
ROOMS ASSIGNED

982
00:39:11,170 --> 00:39:13,472
A SHARED LIFE STARTS NOW

983
00:39:13,739 --> 00:39:15,708
This room isn't so bad.

984
00:39:16,008 --> 00:39:17,409
Mine's not so bad either.

985
00:39:18,711 --> 00:39:19,777
It's not so bad.

986
00:39:19,778 --> 00:39:21,379
It's basically the bathroom.

987
00:39:21,380 --> 00:39:22,982
PASS THE "SECRET" PASSAGE

988
00:39:23,949 --> 00:39:26,451
IT'S THE PREMIUM ROUTE
TO THE BROWN ROOM

989
00:39:26,452 --> 00:39:28,252
- "Jump."
- What do I do?

990
00:39:28,253 --> 00:39:31,422
HIS FUTURE SOMEHOW FEELS MOIST

991
00:39:31,423 --> 00:39:32,691
This is hilarious.

992
00:39:36,328 --> 00:39:39,531
LAUGHS OUT LOUD AFTER A REALITY CHECK

993
00:39:40,532 --> 00:39:41,900
I don't even have a stool.

994
00:39:44,703 --> 00:39:46,104
Not even a stool.

995
00:39:46,105 --> 00:39:47,305
A VANITY WITHOUT A STOOL

996
00:39:47,306 --> 00:39:49,208
I knew something was missing.

997
00:39:49,608 --> 00:39:51,342
There's no thermostat either.

998
00:39:51,343 --> 00:39:53,177
NO SEPARATE THERMOSTAT

999
00:39:53,178 --> 00:39:54,747
No thermostat either.

1000
00:39:55,881 --> 00:39:58,216
The Blue Room has a decent closet.

1001
00:39:58,217 --> 00:39:59,752
- Does it?
- Lucky me.

1002
00:40:00,619 --> 00:40:02,354
Keun-suk, you have a closet?

1003
00:40:04,189 --> 00:40:05,189
DRY LAUGHTER FROM JEALOUSY

1004
00:40:05,190 --> 00:40:07,091
I don't have a closet.

1005
00:40:07,092 --> 00:40:09,360
A CLOTHES RACK INSTEAD OF A CLOSET

1006
00:40:09,361 --> 00:40:10,928
This is a mini move of sorts.

1007
00:40:10,929 --> 00:40:12,031
I know.

1008
00:40:12,765 --> 00:40:14,198
It's a proper move.

1009
00:40:14,199 --> 00:40:16,435
KEUN-SUK STARTS TO GET SETTLED IN
DESPITE ZERO ORGANIZING SKILLS

1010
00:40:18,170 --> 00:40:20,071
The room is spacious
but lacks usable surface.

1011
00:40:20,072 --> 00:40:21,473
IN SEARCH OF ORDER IN DISORDER

1012
00:40:23,142 --> 00:40:27,012
OF COURSE, YOU'D FEEL THAT WAY
IF EVERYTHING IS LAID OUT LIKE THIS

1013
00:40:27,513 --> 00:40:28,614
Get over there, vase.

1014
00:40:29,815 --> 00:40:33,652
PUSHES THE ORIGINAL ORNAMENTS AWAY

1015
00:40:34,553 --> 00:40:39,058
ALL ORNAMENTS IN MY ROOM
SHOULD BE ABOUT ME

1016
00:40:39,892 --> 00:40:40,893
SPRITZ

1017
00:40:41,560 --> 00:40:45,397
EVEN IN CHAOS,
THE ROOM SHOULD SMELL FRAGRANT

1018
00:40:47,099 --> 00:40:51,169
THAT IS THE WAY
OF THE FOREVER ELEGANT PRINCE

1019
00:40:51,170 --> 00:40:52,870
Daniel, did you bring a hairdryer?

1020
00:40:52,871 --> 00:40:54,906
- Want to borrow mine?
- There isn't one in the house?

1021
00:40:54,907 --> 00:40:57,041
- Use mine. I brought it from home.
- Okay.

1022
00:40:57,042 --> 00:40:58,643
- Keun-chan.
- Yes?

1023
00:40:58,644 --> 00:40:59,710
Did you bring a hairdryer?

1024
00:40:59,711 --> 00:41:01,180
- Yes.
- Great.

1025
00:41:01,447 --> 00:41:02,480
- Keun-chan.
- Yes?

1026
00:41:02,481 --> 00:41:04,482
I'm keeping my body lotion
in the bathroom.

1027
00:41:04,483 --> 00:41:05,884
- Feel free to use it.
- Got it.

1028
00:41:06,985 --> 00:41:09,420
<i>Let's keep everything together</i>

1029
00:41:09,421 --> 00:41:11,256
<i>- so we can try different products.
- Sounds great.</i>

1030
00:41:11,590 --> 00:41:14,760
<i>- Shall we keep all toothpastes here?
- Yes, let's keep them here.</i>

1031
00:41:15,828 --> 00:41:19,997
Thanks to the connecting rooms,
we get ample chance to chat.

1032
00:41:19,998 --> 00:41:21,365
It's great. I'm enjoying it.

1033
00:41:21,366 --> 00:41:22,768
Really?

1034
00:41:23,969 --> 00:41:30,843
ANOTHER SET OF CONNECTING ROOMS
ON THE 1ST FLOOR

1035
00:41:31,343 --> 00:41:32,844
<i>It's a first for me.</i>

1036
00:41:32,845 --> 00:41:35,213
You can't call these separate rooms.

1037
00:41:35,214 --> 00:41:37,649
We're almost sharing a single room.

1038
00:41:39,184 --> 00:41:43,454
<i>I can't get to the bathroom
without passing Do-yeon's room.</i>

1039
00:41:43,455 --> 00:41:44,922
DO-YEON'S ROOM
IS ON THE WAY TO THE BATHROOM

1040
00:41:44,923 --> 00:41:46,190
YELLOW: BATHROOM
GREEN: DA-HEE'S ROOM

1041
00:41:46,191 --> 00:41:47,259
<i>So...</i>

1042
00:41:48,227 --> 00:41:50,496
I'd like nothing more
than to knock this wall down.

1043
00:41:50,863 --> 00:41:52,297
I'm serious.

1044
00:41:53,665 --> 00:41:55,933
If it hadn't been
for the bathroom situation

1045
00:41:55,934 --> 00:41:58,837
Do-yeon and I could've
gotten along far better.

1046
00:42:00,372 --> 00:42:03,876
WHAT REPERCUSSIONS WILL
THE SHARED BATHROOM HAVE ON THIS DUO?

1047
00:42:07,212 --> 00:42:08,880
DO-YEON BROUGHT HER FAVORITE CACTUS

1048
00:42:08,881 --> 00:42:10,281
I like it here.

1049
00:42:10,282 --> 00:42:11,950
Stay with your friends.

1050
00:42:12,651 --> 00:42:13,651
GLANCING OVER

1051
00:42:13,652 --> 00:42:15,521
COMING THROUGH

1052
00:42:15,921 --> 00:42:16,922
So cute.

1053
00:42:17,956 --> 00:42:20,858
Hey, this is our new home.

1054
00:42:20,859 --> 00:42:22,861
Get along with your friends, okay?

1055
00:42:24,463 --> 00:42:26,531
- Do-yeon, are you a light sleeper?
- What?

1056
00:42:26,532 --> 00:42:29,133
- Maybe a little bit?
- Once I'm asleep, I don't stir.

1057
00:42:29,134 --> 00:42:31,136
- You don't?
- Yes.

1058
00:42:32,237 --> 00:42:33,505
Is it because of the bathroom?

1059
00:42:33,839 --> 00:42:35,573
Do you visit it a lot?

1060
00:42:35,574 --> 00:42:37,041
It's not that bad.

1061
00:42:37,042 --> 00:42:39,044
- Is it urinary retention?
- That's not it.

1062
00:42:39,845 --> 00:42:42,380
- I'm okay.
- The door may creak and bother you.

1063
00:42:42,381 --> 00:42:44,383
- Oh, I'll be fine.
- That's my concern. You sure?

1064
00:42:45,117 --> 00:42:46,884
It does make an audible creak.

1065
00:42:46,885 --> 00:42:48,187
I'll be fine.

1066
00:42:48,954 --> 00:42:50,121
Don't worry about it.

1067
00:42:50,122 --> 00:42:51,189
THROWN TOGETHER TO BE BESTIES

1068
00:42:51,190 --> 00:42:54,058
- Do you have enough closet space?
- What?

1069
00:42:54,059 --> 00:42:55,928
- You can bring your suitcases over.
- Okay.

1070
00:42:56,461 --> 00:42:57,962
It might get cramped here.

1071
00:42:57,963 --> 00:42:59,264
DECIDED TO SHARE THE DRESSING ROOM

1072
00:43:02,201 --> 00:43:07,306
AWKWARD SILENCE FILLS THE SPACE

1073
00:43:09,575 --> 00:43:11,342
I love <i>Bake Your Dream.</i>

1074
00:43:11,343 --> 00:43:12,977
- Do you follow it?
- I'm crazy about bread.

1075
00:43:12,978 --> 00:43:14,446
I see.

1076
00:43:17,716 --> 00:43:20,218
MBTI: ISFJ

1077
00:43:20,219 --> 00:43:25,557
CONCERNS ABOUT HOUSE SHARE
BEING SHY AROUND STRANGERS

1078
00:43:26,792 --> 00:43:28,392
You vacuumed the place?

1079
00:43:28,393 --> 00:43:30,595
<i>- Did the shoot wrap up?</i>
- Not at all.

1080
00:43:30,596 --> 00:43:34,098
Have you used my credit card today?

1081
00:43:34,099 --> 00:43:35,166
DA-HEE IS SENSITIVE TO NOISE

1082
00:43:35,167 --> 00:43:36,335
OH, RIGHT!

1083
00:43:37,769 --> 00:43:41,139
LEAVING THE ROOM
NOT TO DISTURB DA-HEE

1084
00:43:41,340 --> 00:43:44,675
No, I won't be going home.
I'm going to work straight from here.

1085
00:43:44,676 --> 00:43:47,245
ETIQUETTE IS A MUST IN A HOUSE SHARE

1086
00:43:47,246 --> 00:43:49,648
Someone's coming over to pick me up.

1087
00:43:50,382 --> 00:43:51,383
This place?

1088
00:43:51,850 --> 00:43:55,520
It's in Gugi-dong,
close to Pyeongchang-dong.

1089
00:43:56,855 --> 00:44:00,259
There are no assigned partners.
We're all friends.

1090
00:44:01,693 --> 00:44:04,362
DOES SHE THINK THIS IS A DATING SHOW?

1091
00:44:04,363 --> 00:44:05,631
There's no such thing.

1092
00:44:08,333 --> 00:44:12,237
Mom, this isn't the place
for ulterior motives.

1093
00:44:13,338 --> 00:44:15,873
No, enough about partners.

1094
00:44:15,874 --> 00:44:17,174
You're hilarious.

1095
00:44:17,175 --> 00:44:18,509
It's gross.

1096
00:44:18,510 --> 00:44:20,012
You can stop.

1097
00:44:21,713 --> 00:44:24,449
My mother

1098
00:44:25,083 --> 00:44:26,584
kept on asking

1099
00:44:26,585 --> 00:44:29,553
when I'd start working
on that dating show.

1100
00:44:29,554 --> 00:44:30,921
I went, "Mom, you got it all wrong."

1101
00:44:30,922 --> 00:44:33,924
I told her it's just living together.

1102
00:44:33,925 --> 00:44:34,992
MOTHER'S CUTE MISUNDERSTANDING

1103
00:44:34,993 --> 00:44:38,763
My mother kept asking
if anyone had caught my eye here.

1104
00:44:38,764 --> 00:44:41,266
I told her there was no room
for such ulterior motives.

1105
00:44:41,867 --> 00:44:44,201
She kept telling me
I didn't have to marry

1106
00:44:44,202 --> 00:44:47,339
but I guess deep down,
she wanted to see me settle down.

1107
00:44:48,040 --> 00:44:49,440
- Let's go, Do-yeon.
- We'll get going.

1108
00:44:49,441 --> 00:44:51,809
- See you later.
- See you soon.

1109
00:44:51,810 --> 00:44:53,078
- We're off.
- See you soon.

1110
00:44:54,046 --> 00:44:56,714
FULFILLING HER MOTHER'S SECRET WISH

1111
00:44:56,715 --> 00:44:57,915
It's spacious.

1112
00:44:57,916 --> 00:44:59,284
BY GOING OUT WITH A GUY

1113
00:44:59,651 --> 00:45:01,052
PLEASED

1114
00:45:01,053 --> 00:45:02,721
It's nice to have company.

1115
00:45:04,656 --> 00:45:06,057
It's somehow heartwarming.

1116
00:45:06,058 --> 00:45:07,124
- Really?
- Yes.

1117
00:45:07,125 --> 00:45:08,893
There's a grocery store nearby.

1118
00:45:08,894 --> 00:45:10,028
FRIENDS ON A GROCERY RUN

1119
00:45:10,529 --> 00:45:11,729
When did you get your license?

1120
00:45:11,730 --> 00:45:13,931
Right after my 20th birthday.

1121
00:45:13,932 --> 00:45:14,999
CONFIDENT AT DRIVING

1122
00:45:15,000 --> 00:45:17,102
But I only started
driving myself around

1123
00:45:18,036 --> 00:45:19,838
after finishing
<i>High Kick Through the Roof.</i>

1124
00:45:23,008 --> 00:45:24,809
I'm not familiar with signs,
so please remind me.

1125
00:45:24,810 --> 00:45:25,876
In this situation...

1126
00:45:25,877 --> 00:45:27,212
We should drive on.

1127
00:45:27,779 --> 00:45:29,280
SKILLED DRIVER, WEAK MULTITASKER

1128
00:45:29,281 --> 00:45:30,482
Hey, you're good.

1129
00:45:30,916 --> 00:45:32,350
It's lovely to have a passenger.

1130
00:45:32,351 --> 00:45:33,517
You even check the signs.

1131
00:45:33,518 --> 00:45:35,086
If I had been alone there

1132
00:45:35,087 --> 00:45:36,687
I would've waited a full minute.

1133
00:45:36,688 --> 00:45:38,457
Same. Just to be safe.

1134
00:45:39,224 --> 00:45:41,659
SCREECH

1135
00:45:41,660 --> 00:45:43,027
So I laughed, too.

1136
00:45:43,028 --> 00:45:44,262
EVER THE GENTLEMAN

1137
00:45:44,930 --> 00:45:47,532
AWKWARD TENSION GROWING

1138
00:45:47,833 --> 00:45:48,834
How nice.

1139
00:45:49,968 --> 00:45:52,436
LAUGHING TOGETHER
FOR DIFFERENT REASONS

1140
00:45:52,437 --> 00:45:54,071
<i>On our way to the grocery store...</i>

1141
00:45:54,072 --> 00:45:57,108
<i>You know that feeling
when your heart swells?</i>

1142
00:45:57,109 --> 00:45:59,410
When you get unnecessarily tense.

1143
00:45:59,411 --> 00:46:00,578
That's how it was for me.

1144
00:46:00,579 --> 00:46:01,946
HIS HEART FLUTTERED ON THE WAY

1145
00:46:01,947 --> 00:46:03,381
GLANCING OVER

1146
00:46:03,382 --> 00:46:05,049
- No additional layers?
- None.

1147
00:46:05,050 --> 00:46:06,884
- Did I dress too casually?
- Oh, no.

1148
00:46:06,885 --> 00:46:07,985
You look great.

1149
00:46:07,986 --> 00:46:10,322
UNFILTERED THOUGHTS KEEP ON COMING

1150
00:46:10,889 --> 00:46:13,057
Want to turn on the heated seat?

1151
00:46:13,058 --> 00:46:14,792
- Is Level One okay?
- Me? Yes, that's great.

1152
00:46:14,793 --> 00:46:16,395
- Level One is enough?
- Yes.

1153
00:46:16,895 --> 00:46:18,162
I didn't want you to feel cold.

1154
00:46:18,163 --> 00:46:19,931
SO CONSIDERATE
DESPITE IT BEING ABOVE-ZERO

1155
00:46:20,332 --> 00:46:22,801
I just need to stay away
from the vegetable aisle.

1156
00:46:23,702 --> 00:46:26,036
- Don't forget the dairy section.
- Yes, I should be careful.

1157
00:46:26,037 --> 00:46:28,205
If someone opened the fridge,
I might end up freezing up.

1158
00:46:28,206 --> 00:46:29,273
Is this <i>I am Solo?</i>

1159
00:46:29,274 --> 00:46:32,043
DANIEL SEEMED FLUSTERED AND THRILLED

1160
00:46:32,377 --> 00:46:34,378
Should we call him Yeong-su...

1161
00:46:34,379 --> 00:46:35,813
TOO EMBARRASSED

1162
00:46:35,814 --> 00:46:39,950
Was it a carpool date
of Yeong-suk and Gwang-su?

1163
00:46:39,951 --> 00:46:41,352
ALL SHE CAN DO IS LAUGH

1164
00:46:41,353 --> 00:46:43,521
I don't think
they'll end up together.

1165
00:46:43,522 --> 00:46:44,990
SORRY, MOM

1166
00:46:45,424 --> 00:46:49,760
Are you interested
in getting married?

1167
00:46:49,761 --> 00:46:50,895
- Me?
- Yes.

1168
00:46:50,896 --> 00:46:54,398
I've never set my mind
against marriage

1169
00:46:54,399 --> 00:46:57,335
or felt the wedding fever.

1170
00:46:57,569 --> 00:47:00,104
I sometimes feel
like the clock is ticking

1171
00:47:00,105 --> 00:47:03,073
because most of my friends
have settled down.

1172
00:47:03,074 --> 00:47:04,708
- I get it.
- So many got married.

1173
00:47:04,709 --> 00:47:06,710
A friend of mine
has four kids already.

1174
00:47:06,711 --> 00:47:08,180
A friend of mine has three kids.

1175
00:47:08,880 --> 00:47:10,080
So I keep wondering

1176
00:47:10,081 --> 00:47:14,185
if I'd have to take the initiative
and do something.

1177
00:47:14,186 --> 00:47:16,253
- Like the old days...
- Take the initiative?

1178
00:47:16,254 --> 00:47:18,055
- What does that entail?
- You know.

1179
00:47:18,056 --> 00:47:20,191
I'll do what it takes
like a hyena pack on a hunt.

1180
00:47:20,192 --> 00:47:21,725
Marriage!

1181
00:47:21,726 --> 00:47:24,262
Do I need to do something for it?

1182
00:47:24,896 --> 00:47:27,898
I keep thinking about it,
but I never make a change.

1183
00:47:27,899 --> 00:47:31,035
Are you feeling impatient?

1184
00:47:31,036 --> 00:47:32,102
You're just...

1185
00:47:32,103 --> 00:47:33,771
Some might go,
"I have to get married now."

1186
00:47:33,772 --> 00:47:35,473
- You're not there, right?
- No, I'm not.

1187
00:47:35,474 --> 00:47:38,209
Then again, I'm not there yet

1188
00:47:38,210 --> 00:47:39,810
- but I'm worried about later.
- How?

1189
00:47:39,811 --> 00:47:43,515
What if I end up thinking,
"Why didn't you do something, idiot?"

1190
00:47:44,015 --> 00:47:46,283
What scares me these days
is how fast time goes by.

1191
00:47:46,284 --> 00:47:47,351
I know.

1192
00:47:47,352 --> 00:47:49,186
- That's so true.
- It's insane.

1193
00:47:49,187 --> 00:47:51,288
- It's as if it's got an engine.
- You're right.

1194
00:47:51,289 --> 00:47:53,925
Frankly, when I was in my thirties

1195
00:47:54,326 --> 00:47:56,227
the matter of marriage...

1196
00:47:56,228 --> 00:47:58,230
You could say I was relaxed about it.

1197
00:47:58,763 --> 00:47:59,830
About marriage and stuff.

1198
00:47:59,831 --> 00:48:02,066
- I feel you.
- Like, "I'd get married someday."

1199
00:48:02,067 --> 00:48:04,101
- "I'm still young."
- I thought, "No way."

1200
00:48:04,102 --> 00:48:07,037
"I won't be like this until I'm 42."

1201
00:48:07,038 --> 00:48:08,139
Here I am, 42 years old.

1202
00:48:08,473 --> 00:48:09,474
That's how it is.

1203
00:48:10,275 --> 00:48:11,275
We're here.

1204
00:48:11,276 --> 00:48:12,443
REACHED THEIR STOP IN NO TIME

1205
00:48:12,444 --> 00:48:13,845
So this is it.

1206
00:48:14,279 --> 00:48:15,946
Anyone living alone
would never go here.

1207
00:48:15,947 --> 00:48:17,615
- So true.
- A wholesale retailer.

1208
00:48:17,616 --> 00:48:19,150
They only offer large portions.

1209
00:48:19,684 --> 00:48:21,352
<i>I've never been to a place like this.</i>

1210
00:48:21,353 --> 00:48:22,587
THE SHEER SCALE HERE AMAZES YOU

1211
00:48:23,455 --> 00:48:26,691
HEAVEN OF BULK DEALS

1212
00:48:27,092 --> 00:48:29,793
FAMILIES FLOCK TO THIS PLACE
FOR A BIG HAUL AT A GREAT PRICE

1213
00:48:29,794 --> 00:48:31,962
<i>Convenience stores
have everything I need.</i>

1214
00:48:31,963 --> 00:48:34,231
CONVENIENCE STORE-LOVING SINGLES
FEEL OUT OF PLACE HERE

1215
00:48:34,232 --> 00:48:35,333
Hang on.

1216
00:48:36,101 --> 00:48:37,801
- Napa cabbages, onions...
- Napa cabbages.

1217
00:48:37,802 --> 00:48:38,904
I see onions.

1218
00:48:39,738 --> 00:48:41,272
SURROUNDED BY FRIDGES

1219
00:48:41,273 --> 00:48:43,008
- Napa cabbages...
- Cucumbers.

1220
00:48:43,208 --> 00:48:44,642
Then, carrots...

1221
00:48:44,643 --> 00:48:46,243
DO-YEON ISN'T DRESSED WARMLY

1222
00:48:46,244 --> 00:48:47,411
Aren't you cold, Do-yeon?

1223
00:48:47,412 --> 00:48:49,413
I'm good. Are you feeling hot?

1224
00:48:49,414 --> 00:48:51,883
- It's both, I guess.
- I was messing with you. I'm okay.

1225
00:48:52,617 --> 00:48:53,884
- Here.
- We can grab... What?

1226
00:48:53,885 --> 00:48:57,789
COME ON, WHY PLAY HARD TO GET?

1227
00:48:58,857 --> 00:49:00,157
You sure? I'll take it, then.

1228
00:49:00,158 --> 00:49:01,659
- Go ahead.
- No turning down this time.

1229
00:49:01,660 --> 00:49:03,360
- I'm sweating.
- Thanks.

1230
00:49:03,361 --> 00:49:04,962
SATISFIED

1231
00:49:04,963 --> 00:49:06,163
Go grab a pack of carrots.

1232
00:49:06,164 --> 00:49:07,298
ABASHED

1233
00:49:07,299 --> 00:49:08,432
I like this vest.

1234
00:49:08,433 --> 00:49:10,635
KIND DO-YEON OBLIGES

1235
00:49:14,105 --> 00:49:15,339
About onions...

1236
00:49:15,340 --> 00:49:17,242
Let's grab a whole bag.

1237
00:49:18,410 --> 00:49:20,044
SUCKS IN BREATH

1238
00:49:20,045 --> 00:49:21,112
There are so many of them.

1239
00:49:21,813 --> 00:49:23,113
We have to get rice, too.

1240
00:49:23,114 --> 00:49:24,381
THE MOST IMPORTANT ITEM ON THE LIST

1241
00:49:24,382 --> 00:49:26,917
Everything is in bulk, so...

1242
00:49:26,918 --> 00:49:28,652
The smallest are these 10kg bags.

1243
00:49:28,653 --> 00:49:30,588
I don't see 5kg bags.

1244
00:49:30,589 --> 00:49:32,623
10KG OF UNCOOKED RICE?
THEY RARELY EAT PRECOOKED RICE

1245
00:49:32,624 --> 00:49:34,658
- So we're getting that?
- Yes.

1246
00:49:34,659 --> 00:49:36,695
The six of us
should be able to finish that.

1247
00:49:37,162 --> 00:49:38,796
All right. Rice, checked.

1248
00:49:38,797 --> 00:49:41,298
- So we wait for the octopus?
- That's right.

1249
00:49:41,299 --> 00:49:42,367
5 P.M.
GUGI-DONG HOUSE

1250
00:49:42,934 --> 00:49:44,401
When did you order the octopus?

1251
00:49:44,402 --> 00:49:46,904
I did consider
that there would be six of us

1252
00:49:46,905 --> 00:49:49,807
but I'm not sure
if I ordered the right amount.

1253
00:49:49,808 --> 00:49:51,041
Did you get one?

1254
00:49:51,042 --> 00:49:53,377
Well, yeah. But...

1255
00:49:53,378 --> 00:49:55,914
I love octopus. I really do.

1256
00:49:58,216 --> 00:50:00,384
If we get leftovers,
I can just freeze them

1257
00:50:00,385 --> 00:50:02,519
to use them later.

1258
00:50:02,520 --> 00:50:05,589
I've bought blanched octopus
but never cooked it myself.

1259
00:50:05,590 --> 00:50:07,492
I bet it will taste great.

1260
00:50:07,892 --> 00:50:10,061
WHAT'S THE SECRET
AP DIDN'T GET TO SHARE?

1261
00:50:10,295 --> 00:50:11,462
Cooking octopus?

1262
00:50:11,463 --> 00:50:13,365
- Most cases...
- It feels like too big a challenge.

1263
00:50:13,565 --> 00:50:15,767
- Hey, it's here.
- It's here?

1264
00:50:16,167 --> 00:50:17,701
Wow, I can't wait to see it.

1265
00:50:17,702 --> 00:50:19,671
- It's here.
- It is?

1266
00:50:20,105 --> 00:50:21,205
Did a courier bring it?

1267
00:50:21,206 --> 00:50:22,973
Yeah.

1268
00:50:22,974 --> 00:50:24,308
EXCLAIMS

1269
00:50:24,309 --> 00:50:26,645
- Ta-da.
- This is incredible.

1270
00:50:27,245 --> 00:50:29,380
- Hang on. Isn't it heavy?
- It's huge.

1271
00:50:29,381 --> 00:50:30,448
Let us help you.

1272
00:50:30,682 --> 00:50:31,682
- Just a second.
- Oh, man.

1273
00:50:31,683 --> 00:50:33,984
- It's so heavy.
- Did you order several octopuses?

1274
00:50:33,985 --> 00:50:36,086
- Did you order several octopuses?
- Well...

1275
00:50:36,087 --> 00:50:38,288
- There can't be just one here.
- I'll show you soon.

1276
00:50:38,289 --> 00:50:40,357
- It could be the water inside.
- It can't be one octopus.

1277
00:50:40,358 --> 00:50:42,359
Right, they must've added water.

1278
00:50:42,360 --> 00:50:44,028
- Ice, too.
- Where are we taking it?

1279
00:50:44,029 --> 00:50:46,431
- To the kitchen island?
- What was it again, Soo-jin?

1280
00:50:46,698 --> 00:50:48,065
This is heavier than your wagon.

1281
00:50:48,066 --> 00:50:50,034
- It's heavier than my wagon?
- Yes.

1282
00:50:50,035 --> 00:50:51,435
For real.

1283
00:50:51,436 --> 00:50:52,569
Bring it up here.

1284
00:50:52,570 --> 00:50:54,238
MADE IT TO THE KITCHEN
AFTER MUCH STRUGGLE

1285
00:50:54,239 --> 00:50:55,539
Good job.

1286
00:50:55,540 --> 00:50:57,675
THE BOX IS DEFINITELY HUGE
TO HOLD JUST ONE OCTOPUS

1287
00:50:57,676 --> 00:50:58,743
Hang on.

1288
00:50:59,077 --> 00:51:02,279
DID HE PERHAPS ORDER
SOME OTHER SEAFOOD AS WELL?

1289
00:51:02,280 --> 00:51:04,516
- It's time for the truth.
- What is it?

1290
00:51:05,684 --> 00:51:08,952
- It weighs 18kg.
- What?

1291
00:51:08,953 --> 00:51:10,288
For a single one.

1292
00:51:11,189 --> 00:51:13,525
- I don't buy it. That's unheard of.
- I'm not lying.

1293
00:51:14,659 --> 00:51:15,659
A whopping 18kg?

1294
00:51:15,660 --> 00:51:16,760
FAR TOO MUCH FOR SOLO DWELLERS

1295
00:51:16,761 --> 00:51:18,929
An 18kg octopus?

1296
00:51:18,930 --> 00:51:19,997
ASIA PRINCE MADE A HUGE FLEX PURCHASE

1297
00:51:19,998 --> 00:51:21,498
An 18kg octopus exists?

1298
00:51:21,499 --> 00:51:23,334
EYES FULL OF DISTRUST

1299
00:51:24,169 --> 00:51:25,269
Is it alive?

1300
00:51:25,270 --> 00:51:26,771
- Shall I open it?
- Go ahead.

1301
00:51:27,205 --> 00:51:28,206
- Go ahead.
- Hang on.

1302
00:51:28,740 --> 00:51:29,741
Get ready.

1303
00:51:30,542 --> 00:51:32,844
- That's bound to be gigantic.
- Here we go.

1304
00:51:34,979 --> 00:51:36,981
- I can't see it yet.
- It must be alive.

1305
00:51:38,049 --> 00:51:39,951
Gosh, do I remove...

1306
00:51:40,318 --> 00:51:41,820
Gosh, Keun-chan.

1307
00:51:42,120 --> 00:51:44,888
- It can't be edible.
- It's still alive.

1308
00:51:44,889 --> 00:51:45,956
It's edible.

1309
00:51:45,957 --> 00:51:47,925
- It can't be.
- Come on, it says so here.

1310
00:52:02,276 --> 00:52:04,311
- But it's alive.
- I can take care of that.

1311
00:52:05,245 --> 00:52:06,245
But...

1312
00:52:06,246 --> 00:52:07,713
AP, this is wrong.

1313
00:52:07,714 --> 00:52:08,782
Hold on.

1314
00:52:10,317 --> 00:52:11,918
GIGANTIC

1315
00:52:11,919 --> 00:52:14,154
No!

1316
00:52:14,655 --> 00:52:17,824
ONE PEEK INTO THE NARROW OPENING
TELLS YOU THAT IT'S MASSIVE

1317
00:52:17,825 --> 00:52:20,660
No!

1318
00:52:20,661 --> 00:52:22,229
It's as big as your arm!

1319
00:52:23,730 --> 00:52:25,965
What's the matter?

1320
00:52:25,966 --> 00:52:27,033
DIDN'T GET A CLEAR LOOK

1321
00:52:27,034 --> 00:52:29,202
One suction cup is as big as my fist.

1322
00:52:29,203 --> 00:52:30,303
- Oh, my.
- What do we do?

1323
00:52:30,304 --> 00:52:31,704
What even is this?

1324
00:52:31,705 --> 00:52:32,939
- Is it an octopus?
- It's alive.

1325
00:52:32,940 --> 00:52:34,540
COWARD AHN PLUCKS UP HIS COURAGE

1326
00:52:34,541 --> 00:52:39,011
This thing might end up
sucking our blood.

1327
00:52:39,012 --> 00:52:41,481
It's so gross.
Man, it's something else!

1328
00:52:41,482 --> 00:52:43,015
PLAYING HIDE-AND-SEEK
WITH THE OCTOPUS

1329
00:52:43,016 --> 00:52:44,351
Hey, it's huge.

1330
00:52:45,986 --> 00:52:47,220
Hey, it's huge.

1331
00:52:47,221 --> 00:52:48,788
Hang on. I want to take a picture.

1332
00:52:48,789 --> 00:52:50,156
It's absolutely gigantic.

1333
00:52:50,157 --> 00:52:51,991
Will it grip my finger if I do this?

1334
00:52:51,992 --> 00:52:53,192
- No.
- Hey, it's huge.

1335
00:52:53,193 --> 00:52:54,995
It's trying to eat my finger!

1336
00:52:56,363 --> 00:53:00,199
COWARD AHN BACKS OUT TO SAFETY

1337
00:53:00,200 --> 00:53:01,268
It doesn't bite.

1338
00:53:02,836 --> 00:53:05,438
APPROACHES AGAIN
AT KEUN-SUK'S REASSURANCE

1339
00:53:05,439 --> 00:53:07,440
Dude, it's freaking huge!

1340
00:53:07,441 --> 00:53:09,142
MOVING AWAY FOR THE UMPTEENTH TIME

1341
00:53:09,143 --> 00:53:13,313
Hey, it's coming out!

1342
00:53:13,814 --> 00:53:16,049
IT'S OUT!

1343
00:53:16,517 --> 00:53:18,519
IT BROKE FREE FROM THE BOX

1344
00:53:19,520 --> 00:53:22,856
EVERYONE LOSES THEIR MIND
AS THE OCTOPUS SHOWS ITSELF

1345
00:53:23,891 --> 00:53:25,124
TURNS AWAY

1346
00:53:25,125 --> 00:53:26,926
Guys!

1347
00:53:26,927 --> 00:53:30,396
APPROACHES... THEN RETREATS...

1348
00:53:30,397 --> 00:53:32,232
It's breaking free!

1349
00:53:33,267 --> 00:53:36,135
ALL HELL BREAKS LOOSE

1350
00:53:36,136 --> 00:53:37,537
Hey, it's coming out.

1351
00:53:37,538 --> 00:53:38,704
What do we do?

1352
00:53:38,705 --> 00:53:40,740
PUT A LID ON IT

1353
00:53:40,741 --> 00:53:42,142
Hey, it's breaking out!

1354
00:53:43,377 --> 00:53:46,313
SUDDEN DISPLAY OF TEAMWORK
IN AN EMERGENCY

1355
00:53:46,980 --> 00:53:48,915
STUCK

1356
00:53:48,916 --> 00:53:50,416
Wait, I need to put the arms back in.

1357
00:53:50,417 --> 00:53:52,018
It's so gross!

1358
00:53:52,019 --> 00:53:53,187
Hold on.

1359
00:53:53,554 --> 00:53:55,121
- What do we do?
- It's way too big.

1360
00:53:55,122 --> 00:53:57,591
It's too big.

1361
00:53:58,492 --> 00:54:01,027
CAPTAIN KYUNG OBSERVES

1362
00:54:01,028 --> 00:54:02,962
- What do we do?
- It's way too big.

1363
00:54:02,963 --> 00:54:05,097
SHE THEN PICKS UP A TOOL

1364
00:54:05,098 --> 00:54:06,466
It has a strange texture.

1365
00:54:07,000 --> 00:54:08,901
BUT TO NO AVAIL

1366
00:54:08,902 --> 00:54:11,338
It's coming out again!

1367
00:54:11,638 --> 00:54:12,638
What do I do now?

1368
00:54:12,639 --> 00:54:14,441
Hold on, this isn't right.

1369
00:54:14,541 --> 00:54:15,975
- Let's lure it this way.
- Over here.

1370
00:54:15,976 --> 00:54:17,044
LET'S MOVE TO THE SINK!

1371
00:54:17,744 --> 00:54:19,145
CHAOS STILL REIGNS

1372
00:54:19,146 --> 00:54:21,047
Hold on. What is this?

1373
00:54:21,048 --> 00:54:22,114
- Wait.
- Hey!

1374
00:54:22,115 --> 00:54:23,317
It keeps on coming!

1375
00:54:23,984 --> 00:54:25,051
Look at its face!

1376
00:54:25,052 --> 00:54:26,553
GOING OFF COURSE

1377
00:54:27,988 --> 00:54:29,088
Look at its face!

1378
00:54:29,089 --> 00:54:30,323
- Oh, no!
- Look!

1379
00:54:30,324 --> 00:54:32,459
Just a second!

1380
00:54:33,126 --> 00:54:35,629
INSTEAD OF SORTING IT OUT,
HE CREATED A BIGGER PROBLEM

1381
00:54:36,730 --> 00:54:38,798
IS COWARD AHN CRYING?

1382
00:54:38,799 --> 00:54:41,701
AMID THE RUCKUS,
CAPTAIN KYUNG PUTS ON GLOVES

1383
00:54:41,702 --> 00:54:44,938
IN THE MEANTIME,
DA-HEE IS BLITHELY RECORDING A VIDEO

1384
00:54:45,672 --> 00:54:48,609
DAY ONE
OCTOPUS INCIDENT BROUGHT ON BY AP.MOV

1385
00:54:49,276 --> 00:54:51,511
A DIVERSE GROUP OF HOUSEMATES

1386
00:54:51,979 --> 00:54:55,381
- Hang on, the head.
- Wait a second.

1387
00:54:55,382 --> 00:54:56,482
NO ONE KNOWS WHAT TO DO

1388
00:54:56,483 --> 00:54:57,850
The head's out of the sink!

1389
00:54:57,851 --> 00:55:00,820
- Hang on, the head.
- Wait a second.

1390
00:55:00,821 --> 00:55:01,887
The head...

1391
00:55:01,888 --> 00:55:03,689
IN THE END,
CAPTAIN KYUNG SORTED IT OUT

1392
00:55:03,690 --> 00:55:04,791
The head...

1393
00:55:05,292 --> 00:55:07,127
You got it.

1394
00:55:07,427 --> 00:55:11,064
HUFFING AND PUFFING

1395
00:55:11,665 --> 00:55:13,566
WHAT HAVE I DONE?

1396
00:55:13,567 --> 00:55:14,900
This is just...

1397
00:55:14,901 --> 00:55:16,370
Dude, this can't be edible.

1398
00:55:17,170 --> 00:55:18,305
Hold on.

1399
00:55:19,006 --> 00:55:20,173
My legs have gone weak.

1400
00:55:21,108 --> 00:55:22,808
- It's a giant.
- Its eyes are huge.

1401
00:55:22,809 --> 00:55:24,210
I've never seen an octopus so big.

1402
00:55:24,211 --> 00:55:25,645
- Let's just keep it.
- What?

1403
00:55:25,646 --> 00:55:27,047
We can keep it as a pet.

1404
00:55:28,115 --> 00:55:29,182
Where are its eyes?

1405
00:55:29,850 --> 00:55:31,685
Let's give it a scalp massage
and leave it at that.

1406
00:55:33,687 --> 00:55:36,556
- I think it sensed something.
- Right?

1407
00:55:36,923 --> 00:55:38,090
Let's do this.

1408
00:55:38,091 --> 00:55:39,859
One way or another, I'll get it done.

1409
00:55:39,860 --> 00:55:41,994
This should be the crown of its head,
right between the eyes.

1410
00:55:41,995 --> 00:55:44,298
CHEF KEUN REVIEWS WHAT HE LEARNED
AND GETS TO WORK

1411
00:55:45,399 --> 00:55:46,800
Hang on just a bit longer.

1412
00:55:47,100 --> 00:55:48,100
- I'm almost done.
- It's good.

1413
00:55:48,101 --> 00:55:50,504
CALMLY CONTINUES TO CLEAN THE OCTOPUS

1414
00:55:51,038 --> 00:55:53,140
SHOULD I HELP THEM HOLD IT?

1415
00:55:53,807 --> 00:55:55,341
GRABS AN ARM WITHOUT HESITATION

1416
00:55:55,342 --> 00:55:56,677
How brave.

1417
00:55:57,944 --> 00:56:00,279
HOLDS ONTO AN ARM WITH HER BARE HANDS

1418
00:56:00,280 --> 00:56:01,781
Guys, look.

1419
00:56:01,782 --> 00:56:02,983
Be careful.

1420
00:56:03,583 --> 00:56:05,251
- Do you need gloves, Da-hee?
- I'm good.

1421
00:56:05,252 --> 00:56:06,720
RELAXED DA-HEE, CONCERNED SOO-JIN

1422
00:56:06,953 --> 00:56:08,054
Yes, that's the one.

1423
00:56:08,055 --> 00:56:11,491
THANKS TO DA-HEE'S BAREHANDED ASSIST

1424
00:56:12,192 --> 00:56:13,626
KEUN-SUK BEGINS REMOVING ITS ENTRAILS

1425
00:56:13,627 --> 00:56:14,961
- I'll cut the membrane...
- Good.

1426
00:56:15,595 --> 00:56:17,397
- This is its liver.
- This one?

1427
00:56:19,199 --> 00:56:22,068
TURNING ON THE HYPER-FOCUS MODE

1428
00:56:22,069 --> 00:56:23,370
Okay.

1429
00:56:23,603 --> 00:56:25,638
First off, I'll cut off its arms.

1430
00:56:25,639 --> 00:56:27,274
- One by one.
- Okay, sounds good.

1431
00:56:28,909 --> 00:56:29,909
BAREHANDED ASSISTANT GREW BOLDER

1432
00:56:29,910 --> 00:56:32,446
- Why not cut off this much?
- Let's compromise and do that.

1433
00:56:32,979 --> 00:56:34,981
One arm should be enough
for ten people.

1434
00:56:37,217 --> 00:56:38,719
LAUGHING

1435
00:56:39,252 --> 00:56:40,986
It's thicker than your arm, Da-hee.

1436
00:56:40,987 --> 00:56:42,321
You got that right.

1437
00:56:42,322 --> 00:56:44,825
Okay, I'm getting the hang of it.

1438
00:56:45,192 --> 00:56:47,660
DA-HEE AND KEUN-SUK
MAKE QUICK PROGRESS

1439
00:56:47,661 --> 00:56:49,328
I say that's 100 portions.

1440
00:56:49,329 --> 00:56:50,763
- Agreed.
- It's easily more than that.

1441
00:56:50,764 --> 00:56:52,332
This is no joke, seriously.

1442
00:56:52,966 --> 00:56:54,066
DING-DONG

1443
00:56:54,067 --> 00:56:55,601
- They're back already?
- Who's back?

1444
00:56:55,602 --> 00:56:57,470
- The grocery team.
- So soon?

1445
00:56:57,471 --> 00:56:58,938
- Already?
- That's too soon.

1446
00:56:58,939 --> 00:57:00,006
ARE DANIEL AND DO-YEON BACK?

1447
00:57:01,675 --> 00:57:02,843
Who is it?

1448
00:57:03,276 --> 00:57:05,245
<i>We're here to set up a karaoke booth.</i>

1449
00:57:06,012 --> 00:57:07,847
- A karaoke booth?
<i>- Yes.</i>

1450
00:57:07,848 --> 00:57:10,650
- No way.
- For real?

1451
00:57:11,318 --> 00:57:13,053
- Already?
- How come they're here?

1452
00:57:14,154 --> 00:57:15,688
The karaoke booth arrived.

1453
00:57:15,689 --> 00:57:17,690
- Seriously?
- I don't buy it.

1454
00:57:17,691 --> 00:57:19,392
- Is this for real?
- Did you request one?

1455
00:57:19,393 --> 00:57:20,826
- Yes.
- Seriously?

1456
00:57:20,827 --> 00:57:23,362
But I didn't think
they'd get here so soon.

1457
00:57:23,363 --> 00:57:24,697
HOW DID THIS HAPPEN?

1458
00:57:24,698 --> 00:57:28,401
The basement has a huge empty space.

1459
00:57:28,402 --> 00:57:30,436
<i>- So we're discussing what to add?
- Yes.</i>

1460
00:57:30,437 --> 00:57:31,937
<i>We can bring our hobby projects.</i>

1461
00:57:31,938 --> 00:57:34,407
I have a karaoke machine
in the basement at home.

1462
00:57:34,408 --> 00:57:35,475
Really?

1463
00:57:35,976 --> 00:57:38,310
THE BASEMENT OF DA-HEE'S PLACE

1464
00:57:38,311 --> 00:57:42,548
My only hobby is singing down there.

1465
00:57:42,549 --> 00:57:44,083
- Really?
- Seriously?

1466
00:57:44,084 --> 00:57:47,686
- It'd be nice to keep a booth there.
- If it's possible

1467
00:57:47,687 --> 00:57:49,355
- I'd like to get one.
- You can rent it.

1468
00:57:49,356 --> 00:57:51,691
- I'll look into it.
- Okay.

1469
00:57:51,892 --> 00:57:53,025
<i>I'm going downstairs!</i>

1470
00:57:53,026 --> 00:57:54,493
<i>- See you.
- All right!</i>

1471
00:57:54,494 --> 00:57:55,561
I mean...

1472
00:57:55,562 --> 00:57:57,197
GIGGLES

1473
00:57:57,597 --> 00:57:58,597
They're here.

1474
00:57:58,598 --> 00:58:00,366
- Hello, you got here...
- Hello.

1475
00:58:00,367 --> 00:58:02,535
- I'd like the booth somewhere here.
- I see.

1476
00:58:02,536 --> 00:58:05,070
Where would be the best spot?

1477
00:58:05,071 --> 00:58:06,138
I'd say here.

1478
00:58:06,139 --> 00:58:07,339
- That'd be for the best.
- Here?

1479
00:58:07,340 --> 00:58:10,342
- It's best to keep it in the corner.
- Yes, I agree.

1480
00:58:10,343 --> 00:58:11,444
- Shall we get to work, then?
- Yes.

1481
00:58:11,445 --> 00:58:12,778
- Yes, please.
- Okay.

1482
00:58:12,779 --> 00:58:14,113
Sir!

1483
00:58:14,114 --> 00:58:15,648
Let me know if you have any issues.

1484
00:58:15,649 --> 00:58:16,949
- We'll be upstairs.
- Okay.

1485
00:58:16,950 --> 00:58:18,117
- Thank you!
- No problem.

1486
00:58:18,118 --> 00:58:19,885
I'm curious.
We must see once it's set up.

1487
00:58:19,886 --> 00:58:20,953
- Right?
- Yes.

1488
00:58:20,954 --> 00:58:23,022
GIDDY

1489
00:58:23,023 --> 00:58:24,089
You're so funny.

1490
00:58:24,090 --> 00:58:25,491
AS EXCITED AS SHE CAN BE

1491
00:58:25,492 --> 00:58:28,195
You know, I kind of like this house.

1492
00:58:28,628 --> 00:58:29,663
It's great.

1493
00:58:30,831 --> 00:58:32,565
- Is it going well?
- What?

1494
00:58:32,566 --> 00:58:33,799
We're done with cutting.

1495
00:58:33,800 --> 00:58:34,967
Is the booth all set up?

1496
00:58:34,968 --> 00:58:37,137
- They're on it now.
- They're setting it up now.

1497
00:58:38,338 --> 00:58:40,406
- Look at how much there is.
- We did it in the end.

1498
00:58:40,407 --> 00:58:42,908
We're going to wash it clean now.

1499
00:58:42,909 --> 00:58:44,710
This is unbelievable.

1500
00:58:44,711 --> 00:58:46,178
- Let's begin the massage.
- Shall we?

1501
00:58:46,179 --> 00:58:47,713
STEP 1. RUBBING SALT FOR CLEANING

1502
00:58:47,714 --> 00:58:49,114
Man, the suction cups...

1503
00:58:49,115 --> 00:58:51,852
Each is the size of a Kyoho grape
or a Shine Muscat grape.

1504
00:58:52,385 --> 00:58:53,587
They're huge.

1505
00:58:54,321 --> 00:58:55,655
Should I add some flour?

1506
00:58:56,189 --> 00:58:57,523
- You can do that.
- Good idea.

1507
00:58:57,524 --> 00:59:00,326
We'll need to wash them again anyway.
Might as well do it here.

1508
00:59:00,327 --> 00:59:01,393
SOO-JIN ON FLOUR CLEANSING

1509
00:59:01,394 --> 00:59:02,562
Who knew?

1510
00:59:03,096 --> 00:59:04,196
I had no idea...

1511
00:59:04,197 --> 00:59:05,397
SALT, RINSING, FLOUR

1512
00:59:05,398 --> 00:59:08,034
...so much work would go into it.

1513
00:59:09,002 --> 00:59:10,402
I never knew
an octopus like this existed.

1514
00:59:10,403 --> 00:59:11,671
DEFINITELY NOT A ONE-PERSON JOB

1515
00:59:12,472 --> 00:59:16,409
DA-HEE IS DOING THE DISHES QUIETLY

1516
00:59:16,676 --> 00:59:18,878
- Will you be needing this again?
- Yes.

1517
00:59:18,879 --> 00:59:20,447
HER WORK DOESN'T END HERE

1518
00:59:21,548 --> 00:59:25,885
SHE GOES ON TO CLEAN UP EVERYTHING
WITHOUT A SINGLE WORD OF COMPLAINT

1519
00:59:25,886 --> 00:59:28,087
- You're cleaning endlessly, Da-hee.
- What?

1520
00:59:28,088 --> 00:59:29,388
- Endlessly.
- It's just...

1521
00:59:29,389 --> 00:59:32,025
You three are busy
prepping the octopus.

1522
00:59:32,359 --> 00:59:33,459
You're the best.

1523
00:59:33,460 --> 00:59:34,995
She works so efficiently, too.

1524
00:59:36,630 --> 00:59:38,664
- By the way, AP.
- Yes?

1525
00:59:38,665 --> 00:59:40,366
You said you shower in five minutes.

1526
00:59:40,367 --> 00:59:41,434
Right.

1527
00:59:43,169 --> 00:59:45,704
You're putting more effort
into washing the octopus.

1528
00:59:45,705 --> 00:59:48,708
I wouldn't even wash my own feet
with this much energy.

1529
00:59:50,110 --> 00:59:51,477
WHAT WILL HE MAKE
WITH THE CLEAN OCTOPUS?

1530
00:59:51,478 --> 00:59:53,479
I'm looking forward to the pot rice.

1531
00:59:53,480 --> 00:59:54,713
Right, the octopus pot rice.

1532
00:59:54,714 --> 00:59:56,549
What else was there? Couscous?

1533
00:59:56,550 --> 00:59:58,284
Octopus couscous

1534
00:59:58,285 --> 00:59:59,919
octopus <i>ramyeon</i>

1535
00:59:59,920 --> 01:00:02,688
and octopus skewers.

1536
01:00:02,689 --> 01:00:06,026
If time allows it, I'd blanch it
and serve it the Japanese way.

1537
01:00:06,826 --> 01:00:07,960
Great.

1538
01:00:07,961 --> 01:00:10,630
I can get on to blanching
and chopping it right away.

1539
01:00:11,131 --> 01:00:12,198
Should I set a timer for you?

1540
01:00:12,599 --> 01:00:14,099
Well...

1541
01:00:14,100 --> 01:00:16,436
- Set it for 13 minutes.
- For 13 minutes?

1542
01:00:17,137 --> 01:00:19,138
Hang on. Let me pull up the app.

1543
01:00:19,139 --> 01:00:20,339
A THOROUGH PLANNER

1544
01:00:20,340 --> 01:00:21,407
It was 13 minutes, right?

1545
01:00:21,408 --> 01:00:23,510
ONE GIANT ARM INTO THE POT

1546
01:00:23,843 --> 01:00:25,979
See you.

1547
01:00:26,379 --> 01:00:28,814
We'll keep eating one arm at a time
until we go back home, right?

1548
01:00:28,815 --> 01:00:30,749
- I mean, until the shoot wraps up.
- We could do that.

1549
01:00:30,750 --> 01:00:32,217
- Isn't that the plan?
- That should work.

1550
01:00:32,218 --> 01:00:34,955
- It's not a bad idea.
- Yeah, one arm a day.

1551
01:00:35,522 --> 01:00:38,725
MEANWHILE, SOMETHING IN HER ROOM
IS GIVING DA-HEE TROUBLE

1552
01:00:39,292 --> 01:00:41,293
RATTLES

1553
01:00:41,294 --> 01:00:43,263
POPS

1554
01:00:43,730 --> 01:00:46,066
EXASPERATED

1555
01:00:46,433 --> 01:00:47,666
SHE HEADS OUT

1556
01:00:47,667 --> 01:00:49,134
- Soo-jin.
- Yes?

1557
01:00:49,135 --> 01:00:51,036
- Can you help me with something?
- Sure.

1558
01:00:51,037 --> 01:00:52,137
What's it about?

1559
01:00:52,138 --> 01:00:53,973
EXCUSE US, DO-YEON

1560
01:00:53,974 --> 01:00:55,175
It's just...

1561
01:00:55,542 --> 01:00:57,710
- I brought this with me.
- Okay.

1562
01:00:57,711 --> 01:00:59,578
It might be broken.

1563
01:00:59,579 --> 01:01:01,648
It doesn't release vapor.

1564
01:01:02,148 --> 01:01:03,182
HER HUMIDIFIER IS ACTING UP

1565
01:01:03,183 --> 01:01:04,550
Why isn't it working?

1566
01:01:04,551 --> 01:01:05,985
If you ask me...

1567
01:01:05,986 --> 01:01:07,419
LOOKING AROUND

1568
01:01:07,420 --> 01:01:08,721
Is this the maximum line?

1569
01:01:08,722 --> 01:01:10,656
- Maybe it holds too much water.
- Too much?

1570
01:01:10,657 --> 01:01:12,324
You think so? Let me remove some.

1571
01:01:12,325 --> 01:01:14,493
Humidifiers don't work
if there's too much water.

1572
01:01:14,494 --> 01:01:15,829
- Really?
- Yes.

1573
01:01:18,098 --> 01:01:21,935
WILL IT WORK NOW?

1574
01:01:25,438 --> 01:01:26,439
There we go.

1575
01:01:28,174 --> 01:01:29,943
GASPS

1576
01:01:30,443 --> 01:01:31,978
PACING EXCITEDLY

1577
01:01:32,545 --> 01:01:34,179
YOU'RE THE BEST, SOO-JIN!

1578
01:01:34,180 --> 01:01:35,280
- Sorted, right?
- Yes.

1579
01:01:35,281 --> 01:01:36,649
All right.

1580
01:01:36,650 --> 01:01:37,717
Thank you.

1581
01:01:38,385 --> 01:01:40,986
It was the water all along.
Thank you, Soo-jin.

1582
01:01:40,987 --> 01:01:43,056
- Holler if you need me again.
- Okay, thanks.

1583
01:01:44,391 --> 01:01:47,661
IT'S SO NICE TO HAVE HOUSEMATES!

1584
01:01:48,895 --> 01:01:50,497
Da-hee! Soo-jin!

1585
01:01:50,897 --> 01:01:52,499
Come on, check this out.

1586
01:01:53,299 --> 01:01:54,300
What?

1587
01:01:54,801 --> 01:01:55,834
It's incredible.

1588
01:01:55,835 --> 01:01:56,902
BEHOLD, THE GIGANTIC OCTOPUS

1589
01:01:56,903 --> 01:01:57,970
Amazing.

1590
01:01:57,971 --> 01:01:59,438
- Oh, my.
- It's insane.

1591
01:01:59,439 --> 01:02:01,173
This is incredible.

1592
01:02:01,174 --> 01:02:03,108
- AP, it's the last 20 seconds.
- What?

1593
01:02:03,109 --> 01:02:04,511
- Final 20 seconds?
- Yes.

1594
01:02:05,145 --> 01:02:06,211
WHAT?

1595
01:02:06,212 --> 01:02:07,681
- Final 20 seconds?
- Yes.

1596
01:02:10,016 --> 01:02:12,818
MISSED EACH OTHER BY A PILLAR

1597
01:02:12,819 --> 01:02:14,120
Where are you?

1598
01:02:14,721 --> 01:02:15,989
Where are you?

1599
01:02:16,823 --> 01:02:18,590
How is it? Why did it darken so much?

1600
01:02:18,591 --> 01:02:20,559
DESPERATELY SEARCHING FOR HIS FRIEND

1601
01:02:20,560 --> 01:02:21,727
Where are you?

1602
01:02:21,728 --> 01:02:22,796
I'm over here.

1603
01:02:23,396 --> 01:02:25,231
- You missed him.
- He took a turn.

1604
01:02:25,632 --> 01:02:26,932
- Did you all have a slice?
- Yes.

1605
01:02:26,933 --> 01:02:28,668
THEY'VE NEVER HAD TO LOOK
FOR SOMEONE AT HOME

1606
01:02:29,469 --> 01:02:31,036
KEUN-CHAN'S HOLY-GRAIL INGREDIENT

1607
01:02:31,037 --> 01:02:32,104
It's gotten bigger somehow.

1608
01:02:32,105 --> 01:02:33,673
THE OCTOPUS IS FINALLY OUT

1609
01:02:34,174 --> 01:02:35,941
A COLD PLUNGE TO IMPROVE THE TEXTURE

1610
01:02:35,942 --> 01:02:37,010
My gosh.

1611
01:02:37,677 --> 01:02:39,813
- These should take 20 minutes.
- Full 20 minutes?

1612
01:02:40,246 --> 01:02:41,847
Those are super thick.

1613
01:02:41,848 --> 01:02:43,717
EXTRA LONG TIME
FOR EXTRA LARGE CHUNKS

1614
01:02:43,950 --> 01:02:46,885
- I can hear a car approaching.
- They should be getting back now.

1615
01:02:46,886 --> 01:02:48,788
- Hey, I can see them.
- They're back.

1616
01:02:49,823 --> 01:02:52,224
IT'S STILL COLD OUTSIDE
TO BE IN SHORT-SLEEVES

1617
01:02:52,225 --> 01:02:53,359
Food team.

1618
01:02:54,360 --> 01:02:55,562
Don't they feel the cold?

1619
01:02:57,197 --> 01:02:59,098
- They're real men.
- Must be great to be young.

1620
01:02:59,099 --> 01:03:00,399
TWO YEARS MAKE ALL THE DIFFERENCE

1621
01:03:00,400 --> 01:03:01,700
- Hey, guys.
- They've lost it.

1622
01:03:01,701 --> 01:03:02,836
Hey.

1623
01:03:03,269 --> 01:03:05,337
- I'll take the fresh ingredients.
- Just a second.

1624
01:03:05,338 --> 01:03:07,874
- I want to start cooking right away.
- Be careful. It's heavy.

1625
01:03:08,541 --> 01:03:11,643
- That's too much. Are you sure?
- I can come back for the Coke.

1626
01:03:11,644 --> 01:03:13,412
- I can manage.
- Want to grab this?

1627
01:03:13,413 --> 01:03:14,880
No, but not that one.

1628
01:03:14,881 --> 01:03:17,049
- Wait, I'm good.
- Take them inside.

1629
01:03:17,050 --> 01:03:18,118
Can't take that one, though.

1630
01:03:18,318 --> 01:03:19,452
Why don't you...

1631
01:03:19,953 --> 01:03:21,320
SNORTS OUT A LAUGH

1632
01:03:21,321 --> 01:03:23,288
It's pretty light, Do-yeon.
You'll be surprised.

1633
01:03:23,289 --> 01:03:24,890
It's big but not heavy, right?

1634
01:03:24,891 --> 01:03:26,158
You can add a few more items.

1635
01:03:26,159 --> 01:03:27,427
- Are you sure?
- Yes.

1636
01:03:27,961 --> 01:03:29,595
But not the onions!

1637
01:03:29,596 --> 01:03:31,697
Give me something like bell peppers.

1638
01:03:31,698 --> 01:03:32,998
Haul the onions yourself.

1639
01:03:32,999 --> 01:03:34,199
CARRY THE HEAVY STUFF YOURSELF!

1640
01:03:34,200 --> 01:03:36,169
Here you go.

1641
01:03:36,970 --> 01:03:37,971
Take this, too.

1642
01:03:39,773 --> 01:03:41,508
How am I going to see
where I'm going?

1643
01:03:42,142 --> 01:03:43,742
Okay, I'll take this.

1644
01:03:43,743 --> 01:03:45,010
Leave the rest to me.

1645
01:03:45,011 --> 01:03:46,411
You must be freezing. Go in now.

1646
01:03:46,412 --> 01:03:47,880
WHAT ARE DA-HEE AND SOO-JIN DOING?

1647
01:03:47,881 --> 01:03:48,947
Is the karaoke booth all set?

1648
01:03:48,948 --> 01:03:50,784
- Yes, apparently.
- Really?

1649
01:03:51,317 --> 01:03:52,785
BOUNCY STEPS

1650
01:03:52,786 --> 01:03:55,722
WHEN THEY FINALLY REACH THE BASEMENT
WITH FLUTTERING HEARTS...

1651
01:03:56,156 --> 01:03:58,690
1ST ADDITION TO THE BASEMENT
DA-HEE'S KARAOKE BOOTH

1652
01:03:58,691 --> 01:03:59,793
It's transparent.

1653
01:04:01,161 --> 01:04:02,327
SO MOVED

1654
01:04:02,328 --> 01:04:03,396
It's transparent.

1655
01:04:04,497 --> 01:04:05,698
- It's see-through.
- Yes.

1656
01:04:07,600 --> 01:04:09,034
- Sing a song, Da-hee.
- It's just... What?

1657
01:04:09,035 --> 01:04:10,435
- Go on.
- How does this...

1658
01:04:10,436 --> 01:04:11,671
INSERTING A COIN AS SHE SPEAKS

1659
01:04:14,140 --> 01:04:15,141
You're all set, Da-hee.

1660
01:04:16,176 --> 01:04:17,176
You're all set, Da-hee.

1661
01:04:17,177 --> 01:04:18,545
SHY SMILE

1662
01:04:18,745 --> 01:04:20,679
- I'm so sorry to ask
- Yes?

1663
01:04:20,680 --> 01:04:22,214
but could you go upstairs

1664
01:04:22,215 --> 01:04:24,750
- and check if you can hear me?
- No problem.

1665
01:04:24,751 --> 01:04:26,018
Let me know if you can hear me.

1666
01:04:26,019 --> 01:04:28,021
- I'll make sure to shut this door.
- Thanks.

1667
01:04:29,088 --> 01:04:30,255
GOING UP TO CHECK SOUNDPROOFING

1668
01:04:30,256 --> 01:04:32,125
- Are they back?
- Yes, they're back with groceries.

1669
01:04:32,692 --> 01:04:35,527
The karaoke machine is all set.

1670
01:04:35,528 --> 01:04:36,963
- The coin karaoke?
- Yes.

1671
01:04:37,330 --> 01:04:39,298
- They came over to install it.
- She's singing now.

1672
01:04:39,299 --> 01:04:40,967
- You mean Da-hee? That's wild.
- Yes.

1673
01:04:42,402 --> 01:04:45,805
HER WISH CAME TRUE

1674
01:04:46,506 --> 01:04:48,474
GETTING INTO THE SONG

1675
01:04:49,008 --> 01:04:51,177
STAMPING HER FEET IN EXCITEMENT

1676
01:04:52,645 --> 01:04:56,549
A PASSIONATE PERFORMANCE
FOR A SOUNDPROOF TEST

1677
01:04:58,184 --> 01:04:59,184
RUSHING OUT

1678
01:04:59,185 --> 01:05:00,587
Did you hear me, Soo-jin?

1679
01:05:02,188 --> 01:05:04,023
Did you hear me sing, Soo-jin?

1680
01:05:04,224 --> 01:05:06,091
- Did you hear me, Soo-jin?
- Look at her.

1681
01:05:06,092 --> 01:05:07,192
- No.
- Da-hee!

1682
01:05:07,193 --> 01:05:09,061
Did you hear me sing, Soo-jin?

1683
01:05:09,062 --> 01:05:10,295
Your voice didn't carry.

1684
01:05:10,296 --> 01:05:11,363
- Really?
- Not at all.

1685
01:05:11,364 --> 01:05:13,265
- You couldn't hear me?
- No.

1686
01:05:13,266 --> 01:05:14,367
- Seriously?
- Yes.

1687
01:05:14,667 --> 01:05:16,269
We couldn't hear you
with the doors closed.

1688
01:05:16,870 --> 01:05:18,337
BURST OUT LAUGHING

1689
01:05:18,338 --> 01:05:19,939
Nice, this is great.

1690
01:05:22,008 --> 01:05:24,744
I'll try again with the doors open.
Tell me if you can hear me!

1691
01:05:25,912 --> 01:05:26,912
There she goes again.

1692
01:05:26,913 --> 01:05:28,614
- What if I left the doors open?
- What?

1693
01:05:28,615 --> 01:05:31,317
- Let me know if you can hear me.
- Okay.

1694
01:05:32,285 --> 01:05:34,387
DOORS OPEN WIDE

1695
01:05:35,021 --> 01:05:36,589
- Da-hee.
- Can you hear me?

1696
01:05:37,891 --> 01:05:40,192
CLEARLY AUDIBLE

1697
01:05:40,193 --> 01:05:41,728
- Should we lie to her?
- Da-hee.

1698
01:05:42,128 --> 01:05:44,396
We can't hear a thing.

1699
01:05:44,397 --> 01:05:45,864
We can't hear you.

1700
01:05:45,865 --> 01:05:47,199
Da-hee.

1701
01:05:47,200 --> 01:05:49,002
- What was that, Da-hee?
- We can't hear a thing.

1702
01:05:49,269 --> 01:05:50,836
- Could you hear me?
- No.

1703
01:05:50,837 --> 01:05:52,672
This is incredible.

1704
01:05:53,373 --> 01:05:55,508
SOUNDPROOF TEST COMPLETED

1705
01:05:55,808 --> 01:05:56,809
It's all good now.

1706
01:05:58,177 --> 01:05:59,279
A WIDE GRIN

1707
01:06:00,146 --> 01:06:02,514
SHE'S SO CUTE, ISN'T SHE?

1708
01:06:02,515 --> 01:06:04,317
As long as she's happy, we're good.

1709
01:06:04,817 --> 01:06:06,419
At least someone
has to enjoy it here.

1710
01:06:07,020 --> 01:06:08,654
Gosh, it's freezing.

1711
01:06:08,655 --> 01:06:10,155
Our pantry is filling up.

1712
01:06:10,156 --> 01:06:11,457
That's reassuring.

1713
01:06:12,792 --> 01:06:14,727
I see Keun-suk is our chef now.

1714
01:06:16,696 --> 01:06:19,197
<i>If I do get to be the in-house chef</i>

1715
01:06:19,198 --> 01:06:21,099
<i>I want to show them.</i>

1716
01:06:21,100 --> 01:06:23,169
<i>A meal made by AP is different.</i>

1717
01:06:23,503 --> 01:06:26,772
<i>That's why I came prepared
with five different octopus dishes.</i>

1718
01:06:26,773 --> 01:06:28,140
COUSCOUS, POT RICE,
<i>RAMYEON</i> WITH OCTOPUS

1719
01:06:28,141 --> 01:06:29,475
BLANCHED OCTOPUS, OCTOPUS SKEWERS

1720
01:06:30,410 --> 01:06:33,846
WILL HE BE ABLE TO SERVE
ALL FIVE DISHES AS PLANNED?

1721
01:06:36,649 --> 01:06:38,250
- What's this?
- Is it curry powder?

1722
01:06:38,251 --> 01:06:40,285
This? I'm preparing octopus couscous.

1723
01:06:40,286 --> 01:06:41,687
- Couscous?
- Yes.

1724
01:06:41,688 --> 01:06:42,921
What's couscous?

1725
01:06:42,922 --> 01:06:45,857
Think of it as pasta
formed into a tiny granular shape.

1726
01:06:45,858 --> 01:06:48,093
<i>You can eat with a spoon or a fork</i>

1727
01:06:48,094 --> 01:06:49,494
<i>much like a pasta salad.</i>

1728
01:06:49,495 --> 01:06:52,531
<i>- It's a nice, light appetizer.
- Sounds great.</i>

1729
01:06:52,532 --> 01:06:55,600
Keep this in your refrigerator,
and it will be the perfect snack

1730
01:06:55,601 --> 01:06:57,803
especially when you get peckish
the day before the shoot.

1731
01:06:57,804 --> 01:07:01,039
Even if you finish a full bowl,
your face won't get puffy

1732
01:07:01,040 --> 01:07:02,140
but you'd still feel full.

1733
01:07:02,141 --> 01:07:03,408
THERE'S A FOOD LIKE THAT?

1734
01:07:03,409 --> 01:07:04,476
Brilliant.

1735
01:07:04,477 --> 01:07:05,877
I can eat it for days.

1736
01:07:05,878 --> 01:07:07,547
- Okay, let's keep some.
- I love it.

1737
01:07:08,314 --> 01:07:10,549
You don't boil couscous.
Just pour hot water over them.

1738
01:07:10,550 --> 01:07:12,318
- You soak them?
- Yes, exactly.

1739
01:07:13,252 --> 01:07:14,287
That's so cool.

1740
01:07:15,154 --> 01:07:17,924
NOW, LET'S MOVE ON
TO PREPPING THE OCTOPUS

1741
01:07:18,558 --> 01:07:20,526
TURNING ON THE HYPER-FOCUS MODE

1742
01:07:21,361 --> 01:07:24,063
AP KNOWS HIS WAY AROUND THE KITCHEN
JUDGING BY HIS DELICATE TECHNIQUE

1743
01:07:24,897 --> 01:07:28,368
DICING THE OCTOPUS INTO SMALL CUBES
TO MAKE IT EASIER TO SCOOP THEM UP

1744
01:07:29,202 --> 01:07:31,037
HEY, HE'S PRETTY COOL

1745
01:07:31,571 --> 01:07:33,706
OCTOPUS IS PREPPED IN NO TIME

1746
01:07:34,474 --> 01:07:37,376
ADDING PAPRIKA TO THE SOAKED COUSCOUS

1747
01:07:37,377 --> 01:07:39,212
ADDING OLIVES TO THE SOAKED COUSCOUS

1748
01:07:39,579 --> 01:07:41,647
BELL PEPPERS AND CUCUMBERS
ARE ALSO ADDED

1749
01:07:43,483 --> 01:07:45,051
Hey, I love these vivid colors.

1750
01:07:45,518 --> 01:07:51,090
FOR SEASONING, ADD OLIVE OIL,
SEASONED SALT, AND SOME PEPPER

1751
01:07:51,891 --> 01:07:52,991
TOPPING IT OFF WITH FETA CHEESE

1752
01:07:52,992 --> 01:07:54,192
I'm almost done.

1753
01:07:54,193 --> 01:07:55,260
That looks great.

1754
01:07:55,261 --> 01:07:56,796
ALL EYES ARE ON THE BOWL

1755
01:07:57,497 --> 01:07:59,999
- It looks heavenly.
- So we can eat this as is?

1756
01:08:00,433 --> 01:08:02,035
- Is it a salad of sorts?
- That's it.

1757
01:08:02,802 --> 01:08:04,102
HOUSE SHARE COMES WITH NEW DISHES

1758
01:08:04,103 --> 01:08:06,171
- It looks so pretty.
- This should go down well.

1759
01:08:06,172 --> 01:08:07,807
What's next?

1760
01:08:08,808 --> 01:08:11,009
Should I wash some cucumbers
and the Napa cabbages?

1761
01:08:11,010 --> 01:08:12,111
Yes, please.

1762
01:08:12,979 --> 01:08:15,113
How many cucumbers do you want?

1763
01:08:15,114 --> 01:08:16,415
I SHOULD DO SOMETHING TOO...

1764
01:08:16,416 --> 01:08:17,683
QUALITIES YOU LACK
COOKING SKILLS

1765
01:08:18,117 --> 01:08:19,317
Five cucumbers, please.

1766
01:08:19,318 --> 01:08:20,952
What about the scallions?
Should I chop them up?

1767
01:08:20,953 --> 01:08:22,255
Oh, about the scallions...

1768
01:08:22,488 --> 01:08:25,091
Score them in a cross pattern first

1769
01:08:25,925 --> 01:08:27,427
so we can get little pieces.

1770
01:08:28,227 --> 01:08:29,729
CHUCKLES

1771
01:08:30,830 --> 01:08:31,997
She's clueless about cooking.

1772
01:08:31,998 --> 01:08:33,199
- Oh, right.
- Hang on.

1773
01:08:34,734 --> 01:08:37,403
- Remove the roots first.
- The roots? Got it.

1774
01:08:38,671 --> 01:08:39,671
SHE ONLY REMOVED THE ROOTS

1775
01:08:39,672 --> 01:08:40,840
Great job.

1776
01:08:42,575 --> 01:08:44,377
I'm not entirely clueless, you know.

1777
01:08:44,944 --> 01:08:46,678
- Be careful.
- This is what he wanted, right?

1778
01:08:46,679 --> 01:08:49,014
- Yes.
- Now, how do I score these?

1779
01:08:49,015 --> 01:08:50,850
HOW SWEET

1780
01:08:51,250 --> 01:08:52,617
Why don't you... Hang on.

1781
01:08:52,618 --> 01:08:54,119
WOULD YOU LOOK AT THEM?

1782
01:08:54,120 --> 01:08:55,288
- Be careful.
- Like this...

1783
01:08:55,721 --> 01:08:56,722
Am I doing it right?

1784
01:08:57,190 --> 01:08:58,223
Great job.

1785
01:08:58,224 --> 01:08:59,524
DO-YEON'S CLUMSY BUT HARD WORK

1786
01:08:59,525 --> 01:09:01,793
- Amazing.
- Has she been holding back or what?

1787
01:09:01,794 --> 01:09:02,862
You're doing so well.

1788
01:09:03,796 --> 01:09:05,531
My hands are going to cramp.

1789
01:09:05,731 --> 01:09:06,731
Did you wash your hands?

1790
01:09:06,732 --> 01:09:08,233
Of course, I did!

1791
01:09:08,234 --> 01:09:10,236
- I'm holding a knife.
- Got it.

1792
01:09:10,736 --> 01:09:12,737
JUST SO HAPPY

1793
01:09:12,738 --> 01:09:15,006
- Do I chop off all three onions?
- Just two.

1794
01:09:15,007 --> 01:09:16,909
Gosh, you're the master
of that paring knife.

1795
01:09:18,010 --> 01:09:20,679
SOO-JIN, A 14-YEAR SOLO DWELLER,
TACKLES TASKS ON HER OWN

1796
01:09:20,680 --> 01:09:22,414
Let me wash this large one for you.
Just a sec.

1797
01:09:22,415 --> 01:09:23,483
Okay.

1798
01:09:24,650 --> 01:09:26,051
Did you cut these
with a paring knife?

1799
01:09:26,052 --> 01:09:27,120
Yes.

1800
01:09:27,520 --> 01:09:29,288
- We don't have that many knives.
- Incredible.

1801
01:09:29,789 --> 01:09:31,691
- I have some here.
- Hey, this works pretty well.

1802
01:09:32,158 --> 01:09:33,325
- What the heck?
- He's good.

1803
01:09:33,326 --> 01:09:35,628
SURPRISINGLY SKILLED

1804
01:09:36,596 --> 01:09:37,930
- What the heck?
- He's good.

1805
01:09:39,265 --> 01:09:40,500
Hey, what's all this?

1806
01:09:41,067 --> 01:09:42,768
WOULD YOU LOOK AT THAT?

1807
01:09:43,836 --> 01:09:45,505
Were you perhaps a military cook?

1808
01:09:45,872 --> 01:09:47,506
- My gosh.
- That's so cool.

1809
01:09:47,507 --> 01:09:49,174
What's so special
about chopping some onions?

1810
01:09:49,175 --> 01:09:51,710
Did you have to show off just now?

1811
01:09:51,711 --> 01:09:53,211
- Have some pity for Do-yeon.
- Well, I...

1812
01:09:53,212 --> 01:09:54,746
GLANCING OVER

1813
01:09:54,747 --> 01:09:55,814
Well, I...

1814
01:09:55,815 --> 01:09:57,215
DARN YOU...

1815
01:09:57,216 --> 01:09:59,484
No, Do-yeon's pretty good.

1816
01:09:59,485 --> 01:10:02,287
- Couldn't you have waited?
- You've got skills, Do-yeon.

1817
01:10:02,288 --> 01:10:03,956
- You could've waited.
- It was nothing.

1818
01:10:04,924 --> 01:10:06,324
We need another onion, Daniel.

1819
01:10:06,325 --> 01:10:07,626
- I'll take care of it.
- Okay.

1820
01:10:07,627 --> 01:10:09,662
- Soak them for me, will you?
- Here you go.

1821
01:10:10,696 --> 01:10:13,365
SLOW AND AWKWARD

1822
01:10:13,366 --> 01:10:16,536
QUICK AND RHYTHMICAL

1823
01:10:17,503 --> 01:10:18,503
DANG IT

1824
01:10:18,504 --> 01:10:20,872
Hey, Hyeok.

1825
01:10:20,873 --> 01:10:23,008
- The clattering... It's just...
- My bad.

1826
01:10:23,009 --> 01:10:25,610
- Hey, you've hurt your hand.
- Really?

1827
01:10:25,611 --> 01:10:29,247
- That's a cut.
- You've hurt yourself?

1828
01:10:29,248 --> 01:10:31,082
- Hey.
- Come on, you.

1829
01:10:31,083 --> 01:10:32,951
Why don't I go wash it off?

1830
01:10:32,952 --> 01:10:34,119
GOT CARRIED AWAY AND HURT HIMSELF

1831
01:10:34,120 --> 01:10:38,023
- I can't believe it.
- Let's put a Band-Aid on it.

1832
01:10:38,024 --> 01:10:39,624
- Is that it? I'll go put it on.
- Okay.

1833
01:10:39,625 --> 01:10:41,527
AWAY TO PUT ON A BAND-AID
WITHOUT HIS KNIFE & DIGNITY

1834
01:10:44,397 --> 01:10:46,265
- I got a cut, too.
- Where?

1835
01:10:47,066 --> 01:10:48,166
ANOTHER CASUALTY

1836
01:10:48,167 --> 01:10:49,501
Do-yeon.

1837
01:10:49,502 --> 01:10:50,703
I got a cut, too.

1838
01:10:51,237 --> 01:10:53,105
STARTLED

1839
01:10:53,306 --> 01:10:55,373
- Can I get a Band-aid, too?
- Did you hurt yourself badly?

1840
01:10:55,374 --> 01:10:56,542
No, it's a small cut.

1841
01:10:57,910 --> 01:10:58,911
Let me see.

1842
01:10:59,312 --> 01:11:00,879
Hey, that's a deep one.

1843
01:11:00,880 --> 01:11:02,480
THE GROCERY DUO
BECOMES THE WOUNDED DUO

1844
01:11:02,481 --> 01:11:03,548
I won't need the ointment, right?

1845
01:11:03,549 --> 01:11:05,250
- Let's clean it up first.
- Yeah?

1846
01:11:05,251 --> 01:11:06,318
DA-HEE ON FIRST-AID TREATMENT

1847
01:11:06,319 --> 01:11:07,420
Does it hurt?

1848
01:11:07,753 --> 01:11:08,787
You poor thing.

1849
01:11:08,788 --> 01:11:10,288
- Apply some ointment.
- Splash some peroxide first.

1850
01:11:10,289 --> 01:11:12,091
- I just did that.
- There we go.

1851
01:11:12,358 --> 01:11:14,693
- How's this?
- I'll give you my Band-Aid.

1852
01:11:14,694 --> 01:11:15,760
She's got one already?

1853
01:11:15,761 --> 01:11:17,362
- It stings.
- Are you okay?

1854
01:11:17,363 --> 01:11:18,763
- Come closer.
- I'm good.

1855
01:11:18,764 --> 01:11:19,831
I'll patch you up.

1856
01:11:19,832 --> 01:11:21,099
Did you sterilize the cut?

1857
01:11:21,100 --> 01:11:22,168
All right, then.

1858
01:11:23,603 --> 01:11:25,904
MATCHING BAND-AID RINGS?

1859
01:11:25,905 --> 01:11:27,540
How silly is this?

1860
01:11:28,608 --> 01:11:31,844
THE MAIN CHEF
STARTS PREPARING THE NEXT DISH

1861
01:11:34,146 --> 01:11:35,948
INTEREST PIQUED

1862
01:11:36,215 --> 01:11:38,149
What are you making next?

1863
01:11:38,150 --> 01:11:39,885
I'm adding this to the pot rice.

1864
01:11:40,453 --> 01:11:41,821
WE'RE EXCITED ABOUT THIS ONE, TOO

1865
01:11:42,788 --> 01:11:45,390
LET ME GIVE YOU A TASTE
OF YOUR LIFE WITH THIS PRINCE

1866
01:11:45,391 --> 01:11:46,925
Keun-suk is working so fast.

1867
01:11:46,926 --> 01:11:49,495
THAT'S BECAUSE OUR MEAL IS PRECIOUS

1868
01:11:50,763 --> 01:11:51,964
It looks so good.

1869
01:11:53,032 --> 01:11:55,834
- I actually prepared a little magic.
- What is it?

1870
01:11:55,835 --> 01:11:57,836
- What can it be?
- Splash a little bit of this

1871
01:11:57,837 --> 01:11:59,437
into the pot rice

1872
01:11:59,438 --> 01:12:01,039
and your meal will be perfect.

1873
01:12:01,040 --> 01:12:02,108
What is it?

1874
01:12:02,441 --> 01:12:03,541
Behold

1875
01:12:03,542 --> 01:12:05,044
the bonito soy sauce.

1876
01:12:05,244 --> 01:12:06,745
<i>Let me tell you why it's so good.</i>

1877
01:12:06,746 --> 01:12:10,483
It's because this sauce
contains extra-rich bonito extract.

1878
01:12:10,983 --> 01:12:13,519
This is all you need
to give your dish umami.

1879
01:12:13,986 --> 01:12:16,388
I highly recommend it.
I actually brought it from home.

1880
01:12:16,389 --> 01:12:17,956
- Right.
- He brought a whole bag.

1881
01:12:17,957 --> 01:12:20,392
If you're cooking for one person

1882
01:12:20,393 --> 01:12:22,360
add two spoonfuls to your rice.

1883
01:12:22,361 --> 01:12:23,928
Then, you won't need any seasoning.

1884
01:12:23,929 --> 01:12:25,397
- Great.
- I'd love to try it.

1885
01:12:25,398 --> 01:12:27,733
We have 6 people here,
so I'm adding 12 spoonfuls.

1886
01:12:28,934 --> 01:12:30,368
For the pot rice...

1887
01:12:30,369 --> 01:12:32,137
UMAMI SAUCE

1888
01:12:32,138 --> 01:12:33,906
Add the octopus...

1889
01:12:34,640 --> 01:12:36,374
THEN, ON TO THE STOVETOP

1890
01:12:36,375 --> 01:12:38,911
Cook it just the way you'd cook rice.

1891
01:12:39,345 --> 01:12:40,512
It's pretty simple.

1892
01:12:40,513 --> 01:12:42,181
SO ALL WE'D NEED TO DO NOW IS WAIT?

1893
01:12:43,182 --> 01:12:46,519
I'm going to pan-fry an octopus arm
to use as garnish for the pot rice.

1894
01:12:47,620 --> 01:12:48,887
It smells amazing!

1895
01:12:48,888 --> 01:12:50,489
BUTTER SAUTÉED OCTOPUS TO TOP IT OFF!

1896
01:12:50,923 --> 01:12:54,093
HAD I BEEN AT HOME ALONE,
I WOULD'VE HAD <i>RAMYEON</i> AT BEST

1897
01:12:55,061 --> 01:12:57,762
PRINCE OPERATES IN A DIFFERENT LEAGUE

1898
01:12:57,763 --> 01:12:59,464
- That looks so good.
- It must taste amazing.

1899
01:12:59,465 --> 01:13:00,900
THEY NOW HAVE HIM AS THEIR HOUSEMATE

1900
01:13:01,634 --> 01:13:02,834
FIRING UP HIS PASSION FOR COOKING

1901
01:13:02,835 --> 01:13:05,938
As long as it's cut neatly,
we're good.

1902
01:13:06,472 --> 01:13:08,607
We're having an octopus day.

1903
01:13:09,008 --> 01:13:11,110
- That actually looks pretty.
- I know.

1904
01:13:11,510 --> 01:13:13,012
It's like a cooking vlog.

1905
01:13:13,312 --> 01:13:15,347
Skewer a cherry tomato next.

1906
01:13:15,348 --> 01:13:17,149
- Good.
- Hey, they look neat.

1907
01:13:17,383 --> 01:13:18,950
I might as well use this

1908
01:13:18,951 --> 01:13:21,320
to cook our <i>ramyeon.</i>

1909
01:13:22,355 --> 01:13:24,856
<i>What? If we cook</i> ramyeon <i>with this...</i>

1910
01:13:24,857 --> 01:13:25,924
<i>It will be a knockout.</i>

1911
01:13:25,925 --> 01:13:27,058
RICH OCTOPUS STOCK

1912
01:13:27,059 --> 01:13:28,661
- It's just pure broth.
- Exactly.

1913
01:13:29,395 --> 01:13:31,731
- We already washed it clean.
- Right.

1914
01:13:32,465 --> 01:13:35,601
WHILE POURING THE STOCK
INTO A POT FOR <i>RAMYEON</i>

1915
01:13:36,936 --> 01:13:38,671
SPILLING ALL OVER

1916
01:13:42,708 --> 01:13:43,842
A SHARP INTAKE

1917
01:13:43,843 --> 01:13:46,578
You know, Keun-suk.

1918
01:13:46,579 --> 01:13:48,046
- You're pretty clumsy.
- You got me.

1919
01:13:48,047 --> 01:13:50,248
- I let it all spill.
- Wherever you go

1920
01:13:50,249 --> 01:13:52,418
you leave a trail
for someone else to clean up.

1921
01:13:53,119 --> 01:13:55,187
You need a babysitter, kid.

1922
01:13:56,155 --> 01:13:57,622
You're somewhat...

1923
01:13:57,623 --> 01:13:59,958
It's because this isn't my own place.

1924
01:13:59,959 --> 01:14:01,459
- I'm all confused.
- So that's it, right?

1925
01:14:01,460 --> 01:14:03,395
While watching you cook

1926
01:14:03,396 --> 01:14:04,996
I almost considered
cutting you loose.

1927
01:14:04,997 --> 01:14:06,431
You did trail after me.

1928
01:14:06,432 --> 01:14:08,334
You must be tired of me, too.

1929
01:14:08,901 --> 01:14:10,903
It's like we're playing
cat and mouse.

1930
01:14:12,138 --> 01:14:15,073
I think Keun-suk
caused my hand dermatitis.

1931
01:14:15,074 --> 01:14:16,141
Look at it.

1932
01:14:16,142 --> 01:14:17,476
Hand eczema.

1933
01:14:18,978 --> 01:14:20,478
Watching Da-hee clean everything

1934
01:14:20,479 --> 01:14:24,516
and return all the items I had used
back to their original places

1935
01:14:24,517 --> 01:14:27,052
made me think this must be
what team spirit looks like.

1936
01:14:27,420 --> 01:14:29,687
If Da-hee volunteers to cook someday

1937
01:14:29,688 --> 01:14:31,923
I'd like to assist her
the way she helped me

1938
01:14:31,924 --> 01:14:33,225
following her every step.

1939
01:14:34,059 --> 01:14:35,927
NOW, WE BEGIN COOKING OCTOPUS <i>RAMYEON</i>

1940
01:14:35,928 --> 01:14:37,930
DA-HEE'S CLEANING DUTY NEVER ENDS

1941
01:14:38,831 --> 01:14:40,765
Scallion oil, <i>ramyeon</i> seasoning

1942
01:14:40,766 --> 01:14:43,068
seasoned oil, and then soy sauce.

1943
01:14:43,436 --> 01:14:47,105
PULLING OUT ALL THE STOPS
FOR THE FIRST FAMILY MEAL

1944
01:14:47,106 --> 01:14:49,341
THE HEATED SAUCE
GOES INTO THE OCTOPUS STOCK!

1945
01:14:49,809 --> 01:14:53,077
WITH AP, EVEN <i>RAMYEON</i> IS ELEVATED

1946
01:14:53,078 --> 01:14:56,748
<i>The octopus stock would be very rich
after a whole day of steeping.</i>

1947
01:14:56,749 --> 01:14:58,751
<i>Gosh, they all look fantastic.</i>

1948
01:14:58,951 --> 01:15:00,453
<i>Perfect presentation.</i>

1949
01:15:01,520 --> 01:15:03,456
WHAT A TREAT THIS IS

1950
01:15:03,656 --> 01:15:05,824
<i>- The colors look so healthy, too.
- It does.</i>

1951
01:15:05,825 --> 01:15:06,892
ALL 5 DISHES COMPLETED

1952
01:15:07,293 --> 01:15:08,293
Shall we take some ourselves?

1953
01:15:08,294 --> 01:15:09,394
I HOPE IT TASTES GOOD

1954
01:15:09,395 --> 01:15:10,463
Everything looks delicious.

1955
01:15:10,629 --> 01:15:11,864
Are we ready to eat?

1956
01:15:12,064 --> 01:15:13,431
- Enjoy.
- Thank you for the food.

1957
01:15:13,432 --> 01:15:15,201
- Thanks for your hard work.
- Bon appétit.

1958
01:15:15,634 --> 01:15:17,836
- Good work, everyone.
- Thanks for everything.

1959
01:15:17,837 --> 01:15:18,903
Amazing.

1960
01:15:18,904 --> 01:15:20,905
IN CELEBRATION
OF THEIR FIRST MEAL TOGETHER

1961
01:15:20,906 --> 01:15:22,040
CHEERS!

1962
01:15:22,041 --> 01:15:23,208
Thank you for the food.

1963
01:15:23,209 --> 01:15:24,543
Great work, everyone.

1964
01:15:25,678 --> 01:15:28,947
HERE TO MELT THE DAY'S STRESS

1965
01:15:28,948 --> 01:15:31,183
A COLD GLASS OF BEER

1966
01:15:32,551 --> 01:15:33,552
REFRESHED

1967
01:15:34,553 --> 01:15:36,754
- This is what beer is all about.
- So good.

1968
01:15:36,755 --> 01:15:37,989
ALL THE AWKWARD TENSION

1969
01:15:37,990 --> 01:15:40,692
IS WASHED AWAY

1970
01:15:40,693 --> 01:15:41,893
It's a beer, after all.

1971
01:15:41,894 --> 01:15:44,230
LITTLE BY LITTLE,
THEY GROW COMFORTABLE WITH EACH OTHER

1972
01:15:44,497 --> 01:15:46,031
Way to go, AP.

1973
01:15:46,398 --> 01:15:48,400
- Everything looks so good.
- Absolutely.

1974
01:15:49,401 --> 01:15:51,202
HERE'S OCTOPUS POT RICE,
THE MAIN DISH OF THE DAY!

1975
01:15:51,203 --> 01:15:53,506
My gosh, get a load of this!

1976
01:15:53,839 --> 01:15:55,173
WOW!

1977
01:15:55,174 --> 01:15:56,274
Do you approve?

1978
01:15:56,275 --> 01:15:57,610
Look at this.

1979
01:16:01,113 --> 01:16:02,882
It looks wonderful. What do I do now?

1980
01:16:04,183 --> 01:16:05,251
It looks delicious.

1981
01:16:06,218 --> 01:16:08,019
My gosh, you're something else.

1982
01:16:08,020 --> 01:16:09,754
THE THICK OCTOPUS ARM
GRABS YOUR ATTENTION

1983
01:16:09,755 --> 01:16:11,222
Do you approve?

1984
